Pattern matching in Python vs ScalaPython 与 Scala 中的模式匹配

What is the difference between pattern matching in Python and Scala?Python 和 Scala 中的模式匹配有什么区别？
Bartosz Mikulski 26 Nov 2021 – 8 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2021 年 11 月 26 日 – 阅读时间 8 分钟

When I switched from Scala to Python, the most annoying thing was the lack of pattern matching.当我从 Scala 切换到 Python 时，最烦人的是缺乏模式匹配。

In Scala, we tend to solve multiple problems using the matching operator because such notation makes it easier to work with types such as Option, Either, or Try when we must handle both possible values.在 Scala 中，我们倾向于使用匹配运算符来解决多个问题，因为当我们必须处理两种可能的值时，这种表示法可以更轻松地使用 Option、Either 或 Try 等类型。

Thankfully, since Python 3.10, we finally have structural pattern matching, which works almost the same as the Scala implementation! Let’s take a look at the similarities and differences.值得庆幸的是，从 Python 3.10 开始，我们终于有了结构模式匹配，它的工作方式几乎与 Scala 实现相同！我们来看看相同点和不同点。

Constant matching不断匹配

In both languages, we can use pattern matching to verify whether a variable has the specified value. Of course, Python doesn’t have strict typing. Therefore, we can use values of different types, and the automatic type conversion sometimes gets in the way.在这两种语言中，我们都可以使用模式匹配来验证变量是否具有指定的值。当然，Python 没有严格的类型。因此，我们可以使用不同类型的值，但自动类型转换有时会造成阻碍。

In Scala, I could write the following code to check the value of the x variable:在 Scala 中，我可以编写以下代码来检查 x 变量的值：

x match {
    case 0 => "zero"
    case true => "true"
    case "hello" => "'hello'"
    case _ => "whatever"
}

The equivalent Python code looks like this:等效的 Python 代码如下所示：

match x:
    case 0: print("zero")
    case True: print("true")
    case "hello": print("'hello'")
    case _: print("whatever")

Beware of a trap!!! If the x variable has the value False, 0 will get matched. To solve the problem, we must verify the variable type using a guard expression. I will show the notation in one of the following examples.小心陷阱！！！如果 x 变量的值为 False，则将匹配 0。为了解决这个问题，我们必须使用保护表达式来验证变量类型。我将在以下示例之一中展示该符号。

Sequence matching序列匹配

Scala offers a few ways to match sequence content. For example, we can check the exact length of a sequence and bind the variables by element position:Scala 提供了几种匹配序列内容的方法。例如，我们可以检查序列的确切长度并按元素位置绑定变量：

val ints = Seq(1, 2)
ints match {
    case Seq() => "The Seq is empty!"
    case Seq(first) => s"The seq has one element : $first"
    case Seq(first, second) => s"The seq has two elements : $first, $second"
}

To achieve the same result in Python, we need very similar code:为了在 Python 中实现相同的结果，我们需要非常相似的代码：

ints = [1, 2]

match ints:
    case []: print("The Seq is empty!")
    case [first]: print(f"The seq has one element: {first}")
    case [first, second]: print(f"The seq has two elements: {first}, {second}")

Of course, a common use case of retrieving the first value from a long sequence is also trivial to implement. Let’s start with the Scala code:当然，从长序列中检索第一个值的常见用例实现起来也很简单。让我们从 Scala 代码开始：

seq match {
    case Seq(first, rest@_*) => s"First: $first, rest: $rest"
}

and here is the Python code:这是 Python 代码：

match ints:
    case [first, *rest]: print(f"First: {first}, rest: {rest}")

Matching object fields匹配对象字段

Using pattern matching to match constants and sequence elements would be pretty useless. In Scala, we can use it also to match the fields (and their values) of case classes.使用模式匹配来匹配常量和序列元素是毫无用处的。在 Scala 中，我们还可以使用它来匹配案例类的字段（及其值）。

case class Person(firstName: String, lastName: String)

author = Person("Bartosz", "Mikulski")

author match {
    case Person("Bartosz", last_name) => s"$last_name"
}

To get something similar to a Scala case class in Python, we have to use dataclasses and define the following class:为了获得类似于 Python 中的 Scala 案例类的东西，我们必须使用数据类并定义以下类：

from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class Person:
    first_name: str
    last_name: str

Now, we can instantiate it and try matching the content:现在，我们可以实例化它并尝试匹配内容：

author = Person("Bartosz", "Mikulski")

match author:
    case Person("Bartosz", last_name): print(f"Hi, Bartosz {last_name}")

Matching object fields without dataclasses匹配没有数据类的对象字段

What if we had a standard Python class instead of a dataclass? Would it work?如果我们有一个标准的 Python 类而不是数据类怎么办？会起作用吗？

class NotADataClass:
    def __init__(self, first_name, last_name):
        self.first_name = first_name
        self.last_name = last_name

another_author = NotADataClass("Bartosz", "Mikulski")

match another_author:
    case NotADataClass("Bartosz", _): print("Hi, Bartosz")

Unfortunately, such notation isn’t supported, and when we try running the code, we will get an error: TypeError: NotADataClass() accepts 0 positional sub-patterns (2 given).不幸的是，这种表示法不受支持，当我们尝试运行代码时，我们会收到错误：TypeError: NotADataClass() 接受 0 个位置子模式（给定 2 个）。

However, if we can modify the class definition by adding a special __match_args__ field to tell Python which arguments to use during pattern matching:但是，如果我们可以通过添加特殊的 __match_args__ 字段来修改类定义，以告诉 Python 在模式匹配期间使用哪些参数：

class NotADataClass:
    __match_args__ = ("first_name", "last_name")
    def __init__(self, first_name, last_name):
        self.first_name = first_name
        self.last_name = last_name

another_author = NotADataClass("Bartosz", "Mikulski")

match another_author:
    case NotADataClass("Bartosz", _): print("Hi, Bartosz")

Of course, if we want to match a class imported from someone else’s library, the only thing we can do is wait until they include the __match_args__ in their code, or we can try patching the class definition:当然，如果我们想匹配从别人的库导入的类，我们唯一能做的就是等到他们的代码中包含 __match_args__ ，或者我们可以尝试修补类定义：

NotADataClass.__match_args__ = ("first_name", "last_name")

It will work too. Nevertheless, such patching is quite error-prone, and I don’t recommend doing it.它也会起作用。然而，这样的修补很容易出错，我不建议这样做。

Pattern guards图案护罩

Similarly to Scala, we can use the if statement in the pattern definition to limit the matching:与Scala类似，我们可以在模式定义中使用if语句来限制匹配：

match another_author:
    case NotADataClass(first_name, _) if first_name == "Bartosz": print("Hi, Bartosz")

The condition looks precisely like its Scala equivalent, so let’s move on ;)该条件看起来与 Scala 的等价物完全相同，所以让我们继续;)

Mapping patterns映射模式

Now, let’s take a look at something that doesn’t exist in Scala (or at least it didn’t exist in the last version I was using). We can use pattern matching in Python to check whether a dictionary contains a specified key and value.现在，让我们看一下 Scala 中不存在的东西（或者至少在我使用的上一个版本中不存在）。我们可以在Python中使用模式匹配来检查字典是否包含指定的键和值。

dict_matching = {
    "first_name": "Bartosz",
    "last_name": "Mikulski"
}

match dict_matching:
    case {"first_name": "Bartosz"}: print("Hi, Bartosz")

We can also bind the values to a variable, but it isn’t allowed to bind the keys. The key must always be literal.我们还可以将值绑定到变量，但不允许绑定键。密钥必须始终是字面意思。

match dict_matching:
    case {"first_name": "Bartosz", "last_name": last_name}: print(f"Hi, Bartosz {last_name}")

Matching alternatives匹配替代品

In Scala, we can use pattern alternatives too. The most common usecase is to match multiple exception classes:在 Scala 中，我们也可以使用模式替代方案。最常见的用例是匹配多个异常类：

case _: RuntimeException | _: IOException => ""

Python gives us a similar pattern alternatives notation:Python 为我们提供了类似的模式替代表示法：

match dict_matching:
    case {"first_name": ""} | {"first_name": "Bartosz"}: print("HI!")

No matching found没有找到匹配的

The most shocking difference between Python and Scala is how the pattern matching handles match statements that didn’t match anything.Python 和 Scala 之间最令人震惊的区别是模式匹配如何处理不匹配任何内容的匹配语句。

In Scala, the following match expression throws a scala.MatchError error:在 Scala 中，以下匹配表达式会引发 scala.MatchError 错误：

val x = 0
x match {
    case 1 => "one"
    case 2 => "two"
}

The equivalent Python expression will… do nothing. In Python, pattern matching silently ignores situations when it fails to match anything.等效的 Python 表达式将......不执行任何操作。在 Python 中，模式匹配会默默地忽略无法匹配任何内容的情况。

The hardest thing to remember最难记住的事

As we see, the Python notation is almost identical to Scala pattern matching. For me, the biggest problem is remembering to write match BEFORE the variable name. After all, in Scala, we do it the other way around.正如我们所看到的，Python 表示法与 Scala 模式匹配几乎相同。对我来说，最大的问题是记住在变量名之前写上 match 。毕竟，在 Scala 中，我们的做法恰恰相反。

Domain model in PythonPython 中的领域模型
Bartosz Mikulski 14 Jun 2019 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 6 月 14 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

There are two things I missed when I started working with Python after three years of writing Scala code: types and immutability. Fortunately, it turned out that I missed them only because I did not know Python well enough. There is a way of getting some of that functionality in Python without using external libraries!在编写 Scala 代码三年后，当我开始使用 Python 时，我错过了两件事：类型和不变性。幸运的是，事实证明我错过他们只是因为我对 Python 不够了解。有一种方法可以在 Python 中获得某些功能，而无需使用外部库！

Spoiler alert. Don’t expect too much. It won’t be like Scala types ;)剧透警报。不要期望太多。它不会像 Scala 类型；）

Data classes数据类

Let’s start with types. Using data classes, it is possible to specify the type of a field in a class. The most basic usage looks like this:让我们从类型开始。使用数据类，可以指定类中字段的类型。最基本的用法如下所示：

from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass()
class User:
  name: str
  age: int

Seems to be good, but look what happens when I try to assign a string to the age field.看起来不错，但是看看当我尝试将字符串分配给年龄字段时会发生什么。

>>> u = User('Test', 'aaa')
>>> u
User(name='Test', age='aaa')

It works! It should not work! There is a more powerful way of defining types which does not work either.有用！它不应该工作！有一种更强大的定义类型的方法，但也不起作用。

from typing import NewType
Name = NewType('Name', str)
Age = NewType('Age', int)

@dataclass
class User:
  name: Name
  age: Age

>>> User('Name', 123)
User(name='Name', age=123)

>>> User(Name('Test'), Name(1555))
User(name='Test', age=1555)

I am so disappointed.我很失望。

Functions功能

At least, we can specify the expected type of a function parameter and the type of the returned value! Can we?至少，我们可以指定函数参数的预期类型和返回值的类型！我们可以吗？

It makes no sense, because still, nothing stops me from misusing it…这毫无意义，因为仍然没有什么可以阻止我滥用它......

def name_to_age(name: Name) -> Age:
  return Age(123)

>>> name_to_age(Age(50))
123

Immutability不变性

Fortunately, there is one thing which works as expected. Python elegantly solves the problem of immutability. All we need to do is adding a parameter to an annotation.幸运的是，有一件事按预期工作。 Python 优雅地解决了不变性问题。我们需要做的就是向注释添加一个参数。

@dataclass(frozen = True)
class User:
  name: str
  age: int

>>> u = User('Test', 123)
>>> u.name = 'Another user'
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "<string>", line 3, in __setattr__
dataclasses.FrozenInstanceError: cannot assign to field 'name'

At least something works. What about types? It seems that I can use them only as a part of the documentation. For data validation, https://pydantic-docs.helpmanual.io library must be used.至少有些东西有效。那么类型呢？看来我只能将它们用作文档的一部分。对于数据验证，必须使用 https://pydantic-docs.helpmanual.io 库。

How to use some parts of Domain Driven Design to create maintainable code in Scala?如何使用领域驱动设计的某些部分在 Scala 中创建可维护的代码？
Bartosz Mikulski 11 May 2018 – 9 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 5 月 11 日 – 阅读时间 9 分钟

This article is based on my talk presented at a Java User Group Thüringen meetup in Erfurt, Germany on 26 April 2018.本文基于我于 2018 年 4 月 26 日在德国埃尔福特举行的 Java 用户组图林根会议上发表的演讲。

The road to hell is paved with JavaScript and primitive typesJavaScript 和原始类型铺就了通往地狱的道路

Once upon a time, there was a fearless team of developers who were writing their code in a very usual way. When they needed to pass a number to a method, they used variables of type long. When they needed something represented as text, they used Strings.曾几何时，有一个无所畏惧的开发团队，他们以非常平常的方式编写代码。当他们需要将数字传递给方法时，他们使用 long 类型的变量。当他们需要以文本形式表示的内容时，他们使用字符串。

The classes defined in their code looked like usual Java code, even though they were writing it in Scala. When they needed to store some user data, they created something like that:他们的代码中定义的类看起来像普通的 Java 代码，尽管他们是用 Scala 编写的。当他们需要存储一些用户数据时，他们创建了类似的东西：

case class User {
  firstName: String,
  lastName: String,
  phoneNumber: String,
  emailAddress: String
}

Everything was fine… usually. The code worked correctly… most of the time. The stakeholders were happy… sometimes. There were no bugs… actually, there were bugs. The team felt productive… well, not really.一切都很好……通常。代码在大多数情况下都能正确运行。利益相关者有时很高兴。没有错误……实际上，有错误。团队感觉很有成效……好吧，其实并非如此。

One day, a terrible monster showed up. It was called GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) and it was a nightmare. There were only a few months to prepare all services to the regulations and most of the code were Stringly-typed.有一天，一只可怕的怪物出现了。它被称为 GDPR（通用数据保护条例），这是一场噩梦。只用了几个月的时间就准备好所有符合法规的服务，并且大部分代码都是字符串类型的。

Every time we needed to find the code which processes personal data we needed to search for variable names like: “emailAddress”, “email”, “email_address”, “mail” or even “e_mail”. Ctrl + F was our only hope. There was no EmailAddress type so we could not click the “Find usage” button in our IDE. No, it was just a String and it was used to store email addresses everywhere.每次我们需要查找处理个人数据的代码时，我们都需要搜索变量名称，例如：“emailAddress”、“email”、“email_address”、“mail”甚至“e_mail”。 Ctrl + F 是我们唯一的希望。没有 EmailAddress 类型，因此我们无法单击 IDE 中的“查找用法”按钮。不，它只是一个字符串，用于存储各处的电子邮件地址。

Stringly-typed code字符串类型代码

Consider such normally looking method like that one:考虑这样一种看起来很正常的方法：

public void addToOrder(long orderId, long itemId, long quantity);

We write code like this all the time, don’t we? Is there anything wrong with it? Well, a lot.我们一直在编写这样的代码，不是吗？难道是有什么问题吗？嗯，很多。

What happens when I swap the order of parameters?当我交换参数的顺序时会发生什么？

addToOrder(item, order, quantity);

Did you even notice the difference? I bet in many cases the tests will not help you find the mistake, because the developers are lazy and probably used the same test value for both the item id and the order id.您注意到其中的差异了吗？我敢打赌，在很多情况下，测试不会帮助您发现错误，因为开发人员很懒，可能对商品 id 和订单 id 使用相同的测试值。

What else can I do? I can order -1 item. Yes, I can. It is just a number, so nothing is stopping me from doing something like this:我还可以做些什么？我可以订购 -1 件商品。我可以。这只是一个数字，所以没有什么可以阻止我做这样的事情：

addToOrder(order, item, -1);

What will happen? In the best case, you have some validation code that will throw an exception. In some cases, you may end up with an invalid order in the database. If you code is totally messed up, you will probably pay the customer for one item because he or she order -1 of them ;)会发生什么？在最好的情况下，您有一些会引发异常的验证代码。在某些情况下，您最终可能会在数据库中得到无效订单。如果您的代码完全混乱，您可能会向客户支付一件商品的费用，因为他或她订购了 -1 件;)

One more crazy example. Is there anything stopping me from doing some arithmetic using database identifiers?还有一个疯狂的例子。有什么阻止我使用数据库标识符进行一些算术吗？

(orderId + itemId) * quantity

Common sense, perhaps. Well, as we all know “there is nothing less common than common sense.” ;)也许是常识。众所周知，“没有什么比常识更不常见的了。” ;)

Sure, you can “solve” all of those problems using a lot of if statements. Defensive programming will always help you, won’t it?当然，您可以使用大量 if 语句“解决”所有这些问题。防御性编程总会对你有帮助，不是吗？

public void addToOrder(long orderId, long itemId, long quantity) {
  if(quantity <= 0 || quantity > MAX_ORDER)
    throw new IllegalArgumentException(“foo bar”);
  if(!orderService.orderExists(orderId))
     throw new IllegalStateException(“foo bar”);
  if(!itemService.itemExists(itemId))
    throw new IllegalStateException(“foo bar”);
(...)
}

Do you see how many tests I need to write just to check the parameters? 3 if statements = 6 tests. In this case the first if checks two conditions, so I need 7 tests instead of 6. All of that even before I test the first line of the actual logic of adding an item to the order. I don’t like writing such code, do you?您是否看到我需要编写多少测试才能检查参数？ 3 个 if 语句 = 6 个测试。在本例中，第一个 if 检查两个条件，因此我需要 7 次测试而不是 6 次。甚至在我测试向订单添加商品的实际逻辑的第一行之前就已经完成了所有这些测试。我不喜欢写这样的代码，你呢？

Have you noticed that I need two dependencies just to check parameters? Maybe I do not need them for any other reason. Maybe I have more than one method that needs to verify order id, item id, and the quantity. Hopefully, all of them have the same validation logic. Am I naive? ;) If you write production code for more than two years, you know that every time there are two blocks of code which do the same thing, they do it differently. Every time.您是否注意到我需要两个依赖项来检查参数？也许我出于其他原因不需要它们。也许我有不止一种方法需要验证订单 ID、商品 ID 和数量。希望它们都具有相同的验证逻辑。我天真吗？ ;) 如果您编写生产代码超过两年，您就会知道每次有两个代码块执行相同的操作时，它们会以不同的方式执行。每次。

Can I avoid passing primitive types to methods?我可以避免将原始类型传递给方法吗？

Entities and value objects实体和值对象

What is a variable? What is a value? Is it only a type? Is the number of ordered items just an integer? Or is it something else? In my opinion, every value, every variable consists of its type, constraints, and units of the measurement.什么是变量？什么是价值？它只是一种类型吗？订购商品的数量只是一个整数吗？或者是别的什么？在我看来，每个值、每个变量都由其类型、约束和测量单位组成。

When I look at the number of ordered items I need to know not only that it is an integer, but also that it has an acceptable range of values (more than 0, probably less than some maximal number of ordered items), maybe additional constraints (some customers may be allowed to order more items) and the unit (I need to know that 1 means one item, not one million of items).当我查看订购商品的数量时，我不仅需要知道它是一个整数，而且还需要知道它具有可接受的值范围（大于 0，可能小于订购商品的最大数量），可能还有其他约束（某些客户可能被允许订购更多商品）和单位（我需要知道 1 表示一件商品，而不是一百万件商品）。

How can I encode that knowledge in Java?我如何用 Java 编码这些知识？

Instead of using primitive types, I can create classes for every type of parameters and change the method signature to:我可以为每种类型的参数创建类，并将方法签名更改为：

public void addToOrder(OrderId orderId, ItemId itemId, Quantity quantity)

You may recognise that such parameters are value objects from Domain Driven Design. They have a type, constraints, may contain information about the unit of measurement and are immutable. If I make a mistake and swap parameters, the code will not even compile. That is awesome! I don’t even need to write tests for such cases.您可能会认识到此类参数是领域驱动设计中的值对象。它们具有类型、约束，可能包含有关测量单位的信息并且是不可变的。如果我犯了一个错误并交换了参数，代码甚至无法编译。太棒了！我什至不需要为这种情况编写测试。

In Java you can create such types in this way:在 Java 中，您可以通过以下方式创建此类类型：

public class FirstName {
  private final String value;
  public FirstName(String value) {
    this.value = value;
  }
  public String getValue() {
    return this.value;
  }
}

Note that there is no setter. When I want to modify the value I need to create a new instance. This causes some problems in Java. In Java, if I encode the User data in such way, I need to create methods to modify individual fields of the User object:请注意，没有设置器。当我想修改值时，我需要创建一个新实例。这会导致 Java 中出现一些问题。在Java中，如果我以这种方式编码用户数据，我需要创建方法来修改用户对象的各个字段：

public User withFirstName(FirstName firstName) {
  return new User(
    firstName,
    this.lastName,
    this.emailAddress,
    this.phoneNumber
  );
}

It is problematic because I need to write or generate such methods. The methods need to be tested. You will not want to do that, will you?这是有问题的，因为我需要编写或生成这样的方法。这些方法需要进行测试。你不会想这么做的，是吗？

Scala斯卡拉

Fortunately, writing such code is easy in Scala. In Scala I can create a User case class which is immutable, has automatically generated copy function which is used to create a new instance with some modified fields, and has equals and hashCode methods. Additionally, it works flawlessly with pattern matching.幸运的是，在 Scala 中编写这样的代码很容易。在 Scala 中，我可以创建一个不可变的用户案例类，它自动生成复制函数，用于创建具有一些修改字段的新实例，并且具有 equals 和 hashCode 方法。此外，它与模式匹配完美配合。

case class User(
  firstName: FirstName,
  lastName: LastName,
  emailAddress: EmailAddress,
  phoneNumber: PhoneNumber
)
(...)
user.copy(firstName = FirstName("John"))

Some time ago, I wrote another article about using Scala type system to create the domain model and the beautiful code you can write if you avoid primitive types. Read it if you want to know how to efficiently create classes which do not waste resources at runtime, because additional memory is not allocated. Cool, isn’t it?前段时间，我写了另一篇关于使用 Scala 类型系统创建领域模型以及避免原始类型时可以编写的漂亮代码的文章。如果您想了解如何有效地创建在运行时不会浪费资源的类，请阅读它，因为不会分配额外的内存。很酷，不是吗？

Excuses借口

When I suggest writing code in such way, I hear a lot of excuses. People don’t want to do that. It is something new. Something unfamiliar, strange, maybe even scary.当我建议以这种方式编写代码时，我听到了很多借口。人们不想那样做。这是新事物。一些陌生的、奇怪的、甚至可能令人恐惧的东西。

In my talk, I commented on seven excuses, but let’s focus on one of them. The one that is the most annoying, because at first glance it looks like a valid concern, but when you think about it for a while it does not make sense anymore.在我的演讲中，我评论了七个借口，但让我们重点讨论其中之一。这是最烦人的，因为乍一看它似乎是一个合理的担忧，但当你仔细思考它一段时间时，它就不再有意义了。

More code更多代码

You need to write more classes, even in Scala that is some additional code. You need to call the constructor every time you use them or the companion object, but that is significantly more code than just typing the value of a String or an Integer.您需要编写更多的类，即使在 Scala 中也是一些额外的代码。每次使用它们或伴生对象时都需要调用构造函数，但这比仅键入字符串或整数的值要多得多的代码。

I do not agree with that. If I have types, I do not need a lot of defensive programming. I do not need to validate parameters in every method that gets a String that is supposed to contain a valid and verified email address. I can simply replace the following validation:我不同意这一点。如果我有类型，我就不需要很多防御性编程。我不需要验证每个获取应该包含有效且经过验证的电子邮件地址的字符串的方法中的参数。我可以简单地替换以下验证：

public void sendNotification(String email) {
  if(!emailValidator.isValid(email)) {
    throw new RuntimeException("...")
  }
  if(!emailService.isVerified(email)) {
    throw new RuntimeException("...")
  }
(...)
}

with that code:使用该代码：

public void sendNotification(VerifiedEmail email) {(...)}

Sure, there is a place where I need to create the value and validate the email address, but that is only one place. I do not need to do that in every place where I need an email address.当然，我需要在某个地方创建值并验证电子邮件地址，但这只是一个地方。我不需要在每个需要电子邮件地址的地方都这样做。

I just removed two if statements. That means I can remove at least two tests. This method cannot accept an invalid parameter anymore, I do not need to tests that. Actually, if I wrote the VerifiedEmail constructor/companion object correctly and validate the email when it is created, it is impossible to write tests for invalid usage of the sendNotification method. I cannot even create an invalid instance of email.我刚刚删除了两个 if 语句。这意味着我可以删除至少两个测试。这个方法不能再接受无效的参数，我不需要测试它。实际上，如果我正确编写了 VerifiedEmail 构造函数/伴随对象并在创建时验证电子邮件，则不可能编写针对 sendNotification 方法的无效使用的测试。我什至无法创建无效的电子邮件实例。

What about the validation logic? It is only in one place, in the function that creates a new value of my type. There are no duplicates, no copy/pasting, no silly mistakes and different versions of validation of the same value.验证逻辑怎么样？它只在一个地方，即在创建我的类型的新值的函数中。没有重复、没有复制/粘贴、没有愚蠢的错误以及相同值的不同版本的验证。

Avoid primitive types避免原始类型

What’s the one thing you can do, such that by doing it, everything else will be easier or unnecessary? — “The One Thing” by Gary Keller你可以做哪一件事，这样一来，其他一切都会变得更容易或不必要？ ——加里·凯勒的《唯一一件事》

In my opinion, avoiding primitive types is such one thing that makes everything else easier or unnecessary. Primitive types do not solve any problems, but they create a lot of them.在我看来，避免原始类型是让其他一切变得更容易或不必要的一件事。原始类型不能解决任何问题，但它们会产生很多问题。

If you use separate classes for all of you domain types, you will effortlessly create code that is easy to read and modify. You will make fewer mistakes because some errors are not possible. You do not need a lot of tests when the invalid code does not even compile and when it is not possible to create a value that represents a state that is not existing in your domain.如果您为所有域类型使用单独的类，您将毫不费力地创建易于阅读和修改的代码。你会犯更少的错误，因为有些错误是不可能发生的。当无效代码甚至无法编译并且无法创建表示域中不存在的状态的值时，您不需要进行大量测试。

Get rid of primitive types, please.请摆脱原始类型。

Software engineering软件工程 Scala斯卡拉 Domain Driven Design领域驱动设计

The beauty of properly used statically typed languages正确使用静态类型语言的美妙之处

The real power of programming in Scala is not in mimicking Haskell and overusing monads, but in taking advantage of its type system.Scala 编程的真正威力不在于模仿 Haskell 和过度使用 monad，而在于利用其类型系统。
Bartosz Mikulski 14 Jan 2018 – 4 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 1 月 14 日 – 阅读 4 分钟

The real power of programming in Scala is not mimicking Haskell and overusing monads, but in taking advantage of its type system.Scala 编程的真正威力不在于模仿 Haskell 和过度使用 monad，而在于利用其类型系统。

In Scala, we don’t have an excuse to write “Stringly typed” code, because we can easily create a class for every type in our application using value classes.在 Scala 中，我们没有借口编写“字符串类型”代码，因为我们可以使用值类轻松地为应用程序中的每种类型创建一个类。

class FirstName(val value: String) extends AnyVal
class LastName(val value: String) extends AnyVal
class EmailAddress(val value: String) extends AnyVal

case class User(firstName: FirstName, lastName: LastName, emailAddress: EmailAddress)

Unlike type aliases, those are real classes (at least during compilation) and can be used to increase the readability and enforce the correctness of our code.与类型别名不同，这些是真正的类（至少在编译期间），可用于提高代码的可读性并强制其正确性。

Obviously, when we need the underlying value, we have to write something like: firstName.value, lastName.value, etc. It gets annoying really quickly. What can we do instead of that? If we use Shapeless, we can move the additional code to where we create new instances:显然，当我们需要底层值时，我们必须编写类似：firstName.value、lastName.value 等的内容。它很快就会变得烦人。我们能做什么来代替呢？如果我们使用 Shapeless，我们可以将附加代码移动到创建新实例的位置：

import shapeless.tag
import shapeless.tag.@@

trait FirstNameTag
trait LastNameTag
trait EmailAddressTag

type FirstName = String @@ FirstNameTag
type LastName = String @@ LastNameTag
type EmailAddress = String @@ EmailAddressTag

case class User(firstName: FirstName, lastName: LastName, emailAddress: EmailAddress)

val user = User(
  firstName = tag[FirstNameTag][String]("first name"),
  lastName = tag[LastNameTag][String]("last name"),
  emailAddress = tag[EmailAddressTag][String]("mail@example.com")
)

s"${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}"

How many times did we pass function arguments in the wrong order? Sometimes tests can prevent it, sometimes they don’t. What happens when we have a real domain model? The invalid code does not even compile! It is much better than tests.有多少次我们以错误的顺序传递函数参数？有时测试可以防止这种情况发生，有时却不能。当我们拥有真实的领域模型时会发生什么？无效代码甚至无法编译！这比测试要好得多。

Can we get rid of even more tests and be sure there are no errors? What if we not only create a separate class or type for every domain type, but also for every state or context of a type?我们能否取消更多测试并确保没有错误？如果我们不仅为每个域类型创建一个单独的类或类型，而且还为类型的每个状态或上下文创建一个单独的类或类型，该怎么办？

Imagine that the users of my application can request an email confirmation. Some part of my code can look like that:想象一下我的应用程序的用户可以请求电子邮件确认。我的代码的某些部分可能如下所示：

Will it compile? Unfortunately yes. Will it pass the tests? Maybe, it shouldn’t, but bad tests happen. Will it work correctly? Hell no.它会编译吗？不幸的是，是的。它会通过测试吗？也许，不应该，但糟糕的测试还是会发生。它能正常工作吗？一定不行。

Of course, we can validate the email address. we can even do it twice and repeat the validation in the sendEmail function, hopefully using the same validator. We can, but we all know repeating the validation in two or more places will be the cause of an error at some point.当然，我们可以验证电子邮件地址。我们甚至可以执行两次并在 sendEmail 函数中重复验证，希望使用相同的验证器。我们可以，但我们都知道在两个或多个地方重复验证将在某些时候导致错误。

def validateEmail(emailAddress: EmailAddress): Either[InvalidEmailAddress, ValidEmailAddress] = ???

validateEmail(recipient) match {
  case Left(error) => ???
  case Right(email) => sendEmail(email)
}

Is it better now? Not quite, I can still send spam to everyone because there is nothing to check whether the user verified his/her email address. But types can do even that!现在好点了吗？不完全是，我仍然可以向每个人发送垃圾邮件，因为没有什么可以检查用户是否验证了他/她的电子邮件地址。但类型甚至可以做到这一点！

def sendEmail(emailAddress: VerifiedEmailAddress): Unit = ???

Of course, it is not a silver bullet. Now we need separate DTO classes for our API, data model classes for data storage, and some custom code to map between them and the rich domain model. I think it is worth all of the effort because we encapsulate all of the complexity in types.当然，这不是灵丹妙药。现在，我们需要用于 API 的单独 DTO 类、用于数据存储的数据模型类，以及一些在它们和富域模型之间进行映射的自定义代码。我认为所有的努力都是值得的，因为我们将所有的复杂性封装在类型中。

That code is boring这段代码很无聊

Sure, that code does not look impressive; it’s not complicated; we can hire a new programmer, and that person will quickly be productive because the code is self-documenting.当然，该代码看起来并不令人印象深刻；这并不复杂；我们可以雇用一名新程序员，该人很快就会变得高效，因为代码是自我记录的。

We tend to be excited by complexity; just look at functional programming conference talks. Does anyone want to talk about something simple? No, the more complicated or abstract concept, the better. Really, the better?我们往往会对复杂性感到兴奋；看看函数式编程会议的演讲就知道了。有人想谈谈一些简单的事情吗？不，概念越复杂或抽象越好。真的越多越好吗？

Domain-driven design or creating domain models seems to be too simple. Not easy, just simple. In my opinion, that is exactly why it is so beautiful and useful.领域驱动设计或创建领域模型似乎太简单了。并不容易，只是简单。在我看来，这正是它如此美丽和有用的原因。

When you want to run tests from a single test class using the command line (not from the sbt interactive mode), you probably write this:当您想使用命令行（而不是从 sbt 交互模式）从单个测试类运行测试时，您可能会这样写：

sbt testOnly name.mikulskibartosz.TestClass

This is wrong! It runs all of the tests.这是错误的！它运行所有测试。

The correct way of running a single test class looks like this:运行单个测试类的正确方法如下所示：

sbt "testOnly name.mikulskibartosz.TestClass"

Please remember about the quotation.请记住报价。

Scala structural types with generics具有泛型的 Scala 结构类型

A short example of defining a structural type which matches a generic class定义与泛型类匹配的结构类型的简短示例
Bartosz Mikulski 05 Aug 2018 – 1 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 8 月 5 日 – 阅读 1 分钟

In Scala, if you want to use structural types with a generic class, you must cast the instance to the structural type and import reflective calls.在 Scala 中，如果要将结构类型与泛型类一起使用，则必须将实例强制转换为结构类型并导入反射调用。

Because we have to cast the instance to another type, it is better to define the type alias in a companion object.因为我们必须将实例转换为另一种类型，所以最好在伴生对象中定义类型别名。

import ExampleTest.CanAddElement

import scala.language.reflectiveCalls
import org.scalatest.{FlatSpec, Matchers}

object ExampleTest {
  type CanAddElement = {def add(s: Any): Boolean}
}

class ExampleTest extends FlatSpec with Matchers {
  it should "add an element to the container" in {
    def add[T](container: CanAddElement)(element: T): Unit = {
      container.add(element)
    }

    val set = new java.util.HashSet[String]()
    add(set.asInstanceOf[CanAddElement])("3")
    set.contains("3") shouldEqual true

    val list = new java.util.LinkedList[String]()
    add(list.asInstanceOf[CanAddElement])("3")
    list.contains("3") shouldEqual true
  }
}
Scala斯卡拉 Akka阿卡

Always stop unused Akka actors始终停止未使用的 Akka Actor

Akka actors do not magically disappear when you no longer need them.当你不再需要 Akka 演员时，他们不会神奇地消失。
Bartosz Mikulski 03 May 2017 – 3 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2017 年 5 月 3 日 – 阅读 3 分钟

Recently I came across an easy but interesting problem. An Akka-based application was failing because of an OutOfMemoryError. It was a typical memory leak.最近我遇到了一个简单但有趣的问题。基于 Akka 的应用程序因 OutOfMemoryError 而失败。这是典型的内存泄漏。

The class is an Akka actor that works like this:该类是一个 Akka actor，其工作方式如下：

  • a new instance of the actor is created when a file needs to be downloaded and the actor receives a message which tells it to download the file当需要下载文件并且 Actor 收到一条告诉它下载文件的消息时，会创建 Actor 的新实例
  • the actor stores the reference to the sender参与者存储对发送者的引用
  • it sends an HTTP request to a service它向服务发送 HTTP 请求
  • responses are delivered as messages to the same actor响应作为消息传递给同一参与者
  • the actor can receive either the complete response or a chunk. If it has received a chunk the actor keeps storing the data in a byte array until the whole file is delivered参与者可以接收完整响应或块响应。如果它收到了一个块，则参与者会继续将数据存储在字节数组中，直到整个文件被传递为止
  • finally, when the actor has the entire response, it sends it to the original caller最后，当参与者获得完整的响应时，它将其发送给原始调用者

It can handle only one request, and it is useless after returning the content of the file. That is not a problem. The problem is that it keeps the data in memory even after sending the response back! There are no references to the actor in the application code, but there still is a parent-child relationship defined in the actor system. The actor still exists!它只能处理一个请求，返回文件内容后就没用了。那不是问题。问题是，即使在发送回响应后，它仍将数据保留在内存中！应用程序代码中没有对参与者的引用，但参与者系统中仍然定义了父子关系。演员还存在！

How can I remove an actor?如何删除演员？

Is stopping an actor sufficient to release memory? As I already mentioned, I do not keep any references to the actor besides the ones already existing within the actor system. Does the actor system remove them when I stop an actor?停止演员是否足以释放记忆？正如我已经提到的，除了演员系统中已经存在的引用之外，我不会保留对演员的任何引用。当我停止演员时，演员系统会删除它们吗？

I was trying to find such information in the documentation and Stackoverflow. I failed. To figure out what is going to happen, I created a test application.我试图在文档和 Stackoverflow 中找到此类信息。我失败了。为了弄清楚会发生什么，我创建了一个测试应用程序。

How can I verify it?我怎样才能验证它？

What if I created a straightforward code that uses Akka to waste memory?如果我创建了一个使用 Akka 浪费内存的简单代码怎么办？

import akka.actor.{Actor, ActorSystem, Props}

import scala.util.Random
import scala.concurrent.duration._
import scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext.Implicits.global

case object Produce

object Application extends App {
  val actorSystem = ActorSystem()
  val actor = actorSystem.actorOf(Props[Parent])

  Console.println("Press enter")
  Console.readLine() //I need a few seconds to attach VisualVM to the process ;)

  actorSystem.scheduler.schedule(2 seconds, 200 millis, actor, Produce)
}

class Parent extends Actor {
  override def receive: Receive = {
    case Produce =>
      val child = context.system.actorOf(Props[Child])
      child ! Produce
  }
}

class Child extends Actor {
  val data = new Array[Byte](20000000)

  override def receive: Receive = {
    case Produce =>
      Random.nextBytes(data)
  }
}

When I looked at the memory usage chart in VisualVM I saw that:当我查看 VisualVM 中的内存使用图表时，我看到：

And obviously the error I expected:显然我预期的错误是：

java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space
 at Child.<init>(Application.scala:28)
 at sun.reflect.GeneratedConstructorAccessor2.newInstance(Unknown Source)
 at sun.reflect.DelegatingConstructorAccessorImpl.newInstance(DelegatingConstructorAccessorImpl.java:45)
 at java.lang.reflect.Constructor.newInstance(Constructor.java:423)
 at java.lang.Class.newInstance(Class.java:442)
 at akka.util.Reflect$.instantiate(Reflect.scala:44)
 at akka.actor.NoArgsReflectConstructor.produce(IndirectActorProducer.scala:105)
 at akka.actor.Props.newActor(Props.scala:213)
...

I limited the application memory to only 1GB. Note that the chart does not show 1GB of used memory. The application crashes when it tries to allocate memory, so the chart shows the last value before the crash.我将应用程序内存限制为仅 1GB。请注意，该图表未显示 1GB 的已用内存。应用程序在尝试分配内存时崩溃，因此图表显示崩溃前的最后一个值。

Hypothesis假设

If the actor system removes references to an actor when the actor is stopped, garbage collector will remove the object from memory and the application will not crash. I should notice GC activity on VisualVM charts.如果 Actor 系统在 Actor 停止时删除对 Actor 的引用，则垃圾收集器将从内存中删除该对象，并且应用程序不会崩溃。我应该注意到 VisualVM 图表上的 GC 活动。

All I had to do, was sending a PoisonPill to the Child actor after generating the byte array:我所要做的就是在生成字节数组后向 Child actor 发送一个 PoisonPill：

class Child extends Actor {
  val data = new Array[Byte](20000000)

  override def receive: Receive = {
    case Produce =>
      Random.nextBytes(data)
      context.system.scheduler.scheduleOnce(1 second, self, PoisonPill)
  }
}

Now the program not only keeps running without any errors but also its memory usage chart looks as expected.现在，程序不仅继续运行，没有任何错误，而且其内存使用图表看起来也符合预期。

Conclusion结论

  • Do not forget about references stored internally by the actor system.不要忘记参与者系统内部存储的引用。

  • When you want to get rid of an Akka actor, simply stop it (if you do not keep any references to the actor instance).当您想要摆脱 Akka actor 时，只需停止它即可（如果您不保留对 actor 实例的任何引用）。

  • Some of the actors you create may not be reusable. They won’t magically disappear, you have to remove them.您创建的某些 actor 可能无法重复使用。它们不会神奇地消失，你必须将它们删除。

Genetic algorithms遗传算法

How to assign people to groups in a fair way using genetic algorithms如何使用遗传算法以公平的方式将人们分配到组中

Using Helisa and Jenetics in Scala在 Scala 中使用 Helisa 和 Jenetic
Bartosz Mikulski 21 Jun 2019 – 7 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 6 月 21 日 – 阅读 7 分钟

Some time ago, we had an exciting challenge. Around 80 developers had to be assigned to groups/teams of 8-10 people, and we wanted to have 9 such teams.不久前，我们遇到了一个激动人心的挑战。大约 80 名开发人员必须被分配到 8-10 人的小组/团队，我们希望有 9 个这样的团队。

Every one of the developers could choose to which team they want to be assigned, but due to the constraints (the limited number of groups and the expected size of the group), it was not easy.每个开发人员都可以选择他们想要分配到哪个团队，但由于限制（小组数量有限和小组的预期规模），这并不容易。

Systematic consensus and resistance voting系统共识和阻力投票

The problem has been solved by using the method called systematic consensus. In a nutshell, we wanted to achieve the state that is the least problematic to everyone.这个问题已经通过使用称为系统共识的方法解决了。简而言之，我们希望达到对每个人来说问题最少的状态。

First, we started with resistance voting. In that method of voting, every person assigns scores to their choices, but the score indicates how much they don’t want it. People can assign scores between 0 and 10, but 10 has a special meaning. It means “no way,” “if you assign me there, I quit,” etc.首先，我们从抵抗投票开始。在这种投票方法中，每个人都为自己的选择打分，但分数表明他们不想要它的程度。人们可以给0到10之间的分数打分，但10有特殊的含义。它的意思是“没门”、“如果你指派我去那儿，我就辞职”等等。

When the voting finished we had a score table which looked like this:投票结束后，我们得到了一个分数表，如下所示：

  team AA队 team BB队 team CC队 team DD队 team EE队 team FF队 team GG队 team HH队 team I我队
person 1人 1 0 4 2 6 10 10 10 4 3
person 2人 2 10 10 10 10 10 10 10 0 10
person 3人 3 0 2 10 4 10 10 6 10 8
person 44人 3 3 3 2 1 2 2 4 2

After voting, the people were assigned to the groups. I don’t know what method was used to assign them, but in this article, I am going to show you how to do it using genetic algorithms.投票结束后，人们被分配到不同的小组。我不知道使用什么方法来分配它们，但在本文中，我将向您展示如何使用遗传算法来完成分配。

People gaming the system人们玩弄系统

Quickly we realized that the resistance voting could be easily gamed. Some people were interested in joining only one team, and everything else was unacceptable for them (like “Person 2” in the example above)我们很快意识到，抵抗投票很容易被操纵。有些人只想加入一个团队，其他一切对他们来说都是不可接受的（例如上例中的“第二个人”）

In my opinion, this problem can be solved in at least two ways.在我看来，这个问题至少可以通过两种方式来解决。

No duplicate votes没有重复投票

The first solution is to do not allow duplicate votes. People can vote “10,” but only once. Additionally, it solved the issue caused by people like “Person 4” — people who don’t seem to have an opinion. Saying “I don’t care” is not being flexible and ok with every possible outcome, but instead violates the principles of this method of selecting teams.第一个解决方案是不允许重复投票。人们可以投票“10”，但只能投票一次。此外，它还解决了像“4号人”这样的人——那些似乎没有意见的人——引起的问题。说“我不在乎”并不是对所有可能的结果都灵活和接受，而是违反了这种选择团队方法的原则。

Exponential score指数分数

The second solution is purely mathematical and does not require changing rules or repeating the voting.第二种解决方案是纯数学的，不需要改变规则或重复投票。

I want a method which “punishes” people for not being cooperative and overusing high values, but at the same time I want the emphasize the value of a “10” given by a person who votes “10” only once.我想要一种方法来“惩罚”那些不合作和过度使用高价值观的人，但同时我想要强调只投票“10”一次的人给出的“10”的价值。

First, I need to standardize votes of every person separately. I am going to calculate the standard deviation of scores, and then convert them to z-score.首先，我需要分别标准化每个人的投票。我将计算分数的标准差，然后将它们转换为 z 分数。

For example, in the case of “Person 1,” I have the following scores: 0, 4, 2, 6, 10, 10, 4, 3. The standard deviation of those scores is 3,778594683 and the mean: 5,444444444.例如，对于“Person 1”，我有以下分数：0, 4, 2, 6, 10, 10, 4, 3。这些分数的标准差是 3,778594683，平均值：5, 444444444。

I am going to slighly modify the formula for the z-score because I don’t want a person who voted zero 10 times to break it, so my z-score is:我将稍微修改一下 z 分数的公式，因为我不想让一个 10 次投票为零的人打破它，所以我的 z 分数是：

ZScorei=xi−mean(X)(1+sd(X))ZScorei=xi−mean(X)(1+sd(X))Z S C 哦 r e 我 = X 我 - 米 e A n （ X ） （ 1 + s d （ X ） ） 𝑍 𝑆 𝑐 𝑜 𝑟 𝑒 𝑖 = 𝑥 𝑖 - 𝑚 𝑒 𝑎 𝑛 （ 𝑋 ） （ 1 + 𝑠 𝑑 （ 𝑋 ） ）

This kind of solves the problem of overusing 10s, but the result values are still very similar. There is a small difference between the z-score of a person who voted 10 only once and the abuser of 10s. Additionally, I have to deal with negative values.这样解决了过度使用10s的问题，但结果值仍然非常相似。只投了一次 10 票的人和滥用 10 票的人的 z 分数之间存在微小差异。此外，我还必须处理负值。

Exponential function solves both of those problems.指数函数解决了这两个问题。

Now, I don’t have negative values, and 10s given by abusers have a much smaller impact than a 10 given by a more cooperative person.现在，我没有负面价值观，施虐者给出的 10 分的影响比更合作的人给出的 10 分的影响要小得多。

Genetic algorithms as a solution遗传算法作为解决方案

I have recalculated the scores or changed the rules of voting, but there is a considerable part still missing. I have to assign people to the teams.我重新计算了分数或者改变了投票规则，但还有相当一部分缺失。我必须将人员分配到各个团队中。

In my previous blog post, I described step by step how to use Jenetics and Helisa in Scala, so please take a look at it if anything is confusing.在我之前的博文中，我一步步描述了如何在 Scala 中使用 Jenetics 和 Helisa，所以如果有任何困惑，请看一下。

First, I must encode the developers’ preferences. From the perspective of the algorithm, it does not matter if I use the raw votes, the exponential score, or any other method. The preferences of every person are going to be an Array of numbers.首先，我必须对开发人员的偏好进行编码。从算法的角度来看，我使用原始投票、指数得分或任何其他方法都没有关系。每个人的偏好将是一个数字数组。

def randomPerson(): Array[Int] = Range(0, 9).map(_ => Random.nextInt(11)).toArray

val preferences: Array[Array[Int]] = Array(
    Array(0, 4, 2, 6, 10, 10, 10, 4, 3),
    Array(10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 0, 10),
    Array(0, 2, 10, 4, 10, 10, 6, 10, 8),
    Array(3, 3, 3, 2, 1, 2, 2, 4, 2)
) ++ Range(0, 76).map{ _ => randomPerson()}

def preference(person: Int, group: Int): Int = preferences(person)(group)

When we use a genetic algorithm, the solution is described by a “genotype.”当我们使用遗传算法时，解决方案由“基因型”来描述。

In my case, I have 80 people who can choose one of 9 groups, so I encoded the solution as an array of 80 numbers between 0 and 8. The position in the array denotes the person, and the value indicates to which group the person has been assigned.就我而言，我有 80 个人，他们可以选择 9 个组中的一个，因此我将解决方案编码为由 0 到 8 之间的 80 个数字组成的数组。数组中的位置表示该人，该值表示该人属于哪个组已被分配。

val genotype = () => genotypes.uniform(
    chromosomes.int(min = 0, max = 8, length = 80)
)

Because of the way the solution is encoded, my fitness function takes a List of Integers as an argument and returns an Integer. Calculating the fitness score consists of two parts. First, I have to sum the resistance scores of all developers. Second, I must check if the groups have between 8-10 people.由于解决方案的编码方式，我的适应度函数采用整数列表作为参数并返回一个整数。计算适应度分数由两部分组成。首先，我必须将所有开发人员的抵抗分数相加。其次，我必须检查小组人数是否在 8-10 人之间。

I am going to sum the resistance scores of people assigned to groups. To put emphasis on the group size, I am going to raise 10 to the power of the number of unmet size constraints in every group and add the results to the resistance score.我将对分配到各组的人的抵抗力分数进行求和。为了强调小组规模，我将每组中未满足规模限制的数量乘以 10 次方，并将结果添加到阻力分数中。

def fitness(solution: List[Int]): Long = {
    val idealSizeOfGroup = 9

    val peopleResistanceScore = solution
        .zipWithIndex
        .map {
            case (group, person) => preference(person, group)
        }
        .sum

    val groupSizeResistanceScore = solution
        .groupBy(identity)
        .mapValues(peopleInTheGroup =>
            //if you used exponential score, you should change the base to 100
            Math.pow(10, Math.abs(peopleInTheGroup.length - idealSizeOfGroup)))
        .values
        .sum

    peopleResistanceScore.toLong + groupSizeResistanceScore.toLong
}

Because Helisa provides only implicit decoders for case classes and I used a List as the parameter of my fitness function, I have to define my decoder which converts an IntegerGene to a List of Ints.因为 Helisa 只为案例类提供隐式解码器，并且我使用 List 作为适应度函数的参数，所以我必须定义将 IntegerGene 转换为 Int 列表的解码器。

import com.softwaremill.helisa.api.convert.Decoder
import io.jenetics.IntegerGene

implicit def decoder = new Decoder[List[Int], IntegerGene] {
    import scala.collection.JavaConverters._

    def decode(genotype: Genotype[IntegerGene]): Option[List[Int]] = {
      val list = genotype.iterator().asScala.flatMap(_.toSeq.asScala.map(_.getAllele.toInt)).toList
      if(list.isEmpty) None else Some(list)
    }
}

When all of that is ready, I can run the Evolver to get the solution.当所有这些都准备好后，我可以运行 Evolver 来获得解决方案。

val evolver = Evolver(fitness, genotype)
    .minimizing()
    .populationSize(500)
    .survivorsSelector(selectors.tournament(20))
    .survivorsSize(20)
    .offspringSelector(selectors.rouletteWheel())
    .geneticOperators(operators.crossover.singlePoint(), operators.mutator.swap())
    .build()

val best = evolver.streamScalaStdLib().drop(5000).head

Console.println(best.bestFitness)

val bestSolution = best.bestPhenotype.head

Console.println(
    bestSolution
        .groupBy(identity)
        .mapValues(_.length)
        .toList
        .sortBy(_._1)
        .mkString(",")
    )

Genetic algorithms遗传算法

Genetic algorithms in Scala - solving optimization problemsScala 中的遗传算法 - 解决优化问题

Using Helisa and Jenetics to help Fallout players使用 Helisa 和 Jenetics 来帮助《辐射》玩家
Bartosz Mikulski 19 Jun 2019 – 10 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 6 月 19 日 – 阅读 10 分钟

In this article, I am going to describe the usage of genetic algorithms in Scala. Genetic algorithms are used to solve optimization problems. It is a class of problems that don’t have an obvious solution, and there is no easy way to improve an existing solution.在本文中，我将介绍遗传算法在 Scala 中的用法。遗传算法用于解决优化问题。这是一类没有明显解决方案的问题，并且没有简单的方法来改进现有的解决方案。

In general, there is a global maximum, which is the best possible solution and many local maximums, so it is precisely the same situation as training a machine learning model or a neural network.一般来说，存在一个全局最大值，即可能的最佳解，还有许多局部最大值，因此这与训练机器学习模型或神经网络的情况完全相同。

Genetic algorithms mimic evolution. The potential solution of a problem is described as a genotype in which all genes describe a part of a solution.遗传算法模仿进化。问题的潜在解决方案被描述为基因型，其中所有基因都描述了解决方案的一部分。

The crucial part of the algorithm is its “fitness” function. The value produced by the function tells how well the genotype solves the problem. It is the equivalent of an evaluation metric used in machine learning.该算法的关键部分是其“适应度”功能。函数产生的值表明基因型解决问题的程度。它相当于机器学习中使用的评估指标。

Knapsack problem背包问题

The most known problem solved by optimization algorithms is the Knapsack problem. The details depend on the person who is telling the story, but I usually heard this version.优化算法解决的最著名的问题是背包问题。细节取决于讲故事的人，但我通常听到这个版本。

A thief broke into a house. He has only a small backpack, so he cannot take everything. Therefore the thief must decide which items he should steal. The thief knows the value of items and their weight. The goal of the optimization algorithm is to tell which items should the thief take to maximize the value of the stolen loot, but the maximal capacity of the backpack cannot be exceeded.一个小偷闯入了一所房子。他只有一个小背包，所以他不能带所有东西。因此，小偷必须决定他应该偷哪些物品。小偷知道物品的价值及其重量。优化算法的目标是告诉小偷应该拿走哪些物品来最大化被盗战利品的价值，但不能超过背包的最大容量。

Example例子

I am going to do something very similar. Let’s imagine that we are playing a computer game (for example Fallout 2, because we like old, good games). We have just won a battle with multiple enemies, and we started looting their corpses. We found many armors, and we want to sell them. Unfortunately, there is no way to take all of them because they are too heavy, so we must decide which armors should we take to maximize the amount we get when we sell them.我要做一些非常相似的事情。假设我们正在玩一款电脑游戏（例如《辐射 2》，因为我们喜欢老的好游戏）。我们刚刚赢得了一场与多个敌人的战斗，我们开始掠夺他们的尸体。我们发现了很多盔甲，我们想卖掉它们。不幸的是，我们无法把它们全部拿走，因为它们太重了，所以我们必须决定应该拿走哪些盔甲，才能最大限度地提高出售它们时获得的数量。

Problem问题

To solve the problem, I am going to use the Jenetics library with a Scala wrapper called Helisa. In the first step, I have to define the problem space. I have some items on the ground. I can distinguish between the types of items. I know how many of them are there. I can check how much their weight and I know the armor prices.为了解决这个问题，我将使用 Jenetics 库和一个名为 Helisa 的 Scala 包装器。第一步，我必须定义问题空间。我在地上有一些物品。我可以区分物品的类型。我知道他们有多少人。我可以检查他们的重量，并且我知道盔甲的价格。

Solution解决方案

I have already discovered one of the constraints. The number of available armors. I can’t take two Advanced Power Armors with me because there is only one. The other constraint is the total weight of the items. In Fallout 2, the maximal weight of items a player can carry is defined as 25 + (player’s strength * 25) lbs.我已经发现了其中的限制之一。可用装甲的数量。我不能随身携带两件高级动力装甲，因为只有一件。另一个限制是物品的总重量。在《辐射 2》中，玩家可以携带的物品的最大重量定义为 25 +（玩家的力量 * 25）磅。

I know everything I need, so now it is the time to start defining the schema of the solution. I start with a backpack. It is a case class that tells me how many armors of a particular type I have decided to take. For convenience, I also include the maximal weight as a field in this case class.我知道我需要的一切，所以现在是开始定义解决方案架构的时候了。我从背包开始。这是一个案例类，告诉我我决定购买多少特定类型的盔甲。为了方便起见，我还将最大重量作为字段包含在该案例类中。

Helisa and Jenetics海莉莎和珍妮蒂斯

Genotype基因型

That was the problem and solution representation is Scala. Now, I can start using Helisa to configure Jenetics and its genetic algorithm.这就是问题所在，解决方案的代表是 Scala。现在，我可以开始使用 Helisa 来配置 Jenetics 及其遗传算法。

First, I define the genotype. It is the representation of the solution and its structure must fit the Backpack case class I defined above. Also, I encode some constraints using the genotype. I know that there is 5 robes, 5 leather jackets, 5 leather armors, and 5 combat leather armors. Those are also the first 4 fields of my case class, so I encode them all as one chromosome which can have values between 0 and 5.首先，我定义基因型。它是解决方案的表示，其结构必须适合我上面定义的 Backpack 案例类。另外，我使用基因型对一些约束进行编码。我知道有5件长袍，5件皮夹克，5件皮甲，5件战斗皮甲。这些也是我的案例类的前 4 个字段，因此我将它们全部编码为一条染色体，其值可以在 0 到 5 之间。

chromosomes.int(0, 5, length = 4)

There are 2 leather armors Mk. 2 and 2 metal armors. So the next chromosome encodes two fields which can have values between 0 and 2.有 2 件皮甲 Mk. 2和2金属装甲。因此，下一条染色体编码两个字段，其值可以在 0 到 2 之间。

chromosomes.int(0, 2, length = 2)

The total length of the genotype (the sum of the chromosome lengths) must be equal to the number of fields in the case class.基因型的总长度（染色体长度之和）必须等于病例类中的字段数。

Fitness function again再次健身功能

After that, I implement the fitness function. It takes a Backpack as an argument and returns an integer which denotes the value of the items in the backpack.之后，我实现了健身功能。它以背包作为参数并返回一个整数，表示背包中物品的值。

There is one caveat, I also need to take into account invalid solutions. There are genotype validators, but I did not manage to make them work as I expect, so instead of that, I included validation in my fitness score. If I find a way to use the validators to impose constraints, I will write an article about it ;)有一个警告，我还需要考虑无效的解决方案。有基因型验证器，但我没有设法让它们按我的预期工作，因此我将验证纳入了我的健康得分中。如果我找到一种使用验证器施加约束的方法，我将写一篇关于它的文章；）

A solution that exceeds the maximal weight of items or contains more items than it is possible to obtain must get a low fitness score. So the function returns the total value if the solution is valid and zero if the constraints have been violated.超过项目最大重量或包含的项目数量多于可能获得的解决方案必须获得较低的适应度分数。因此，如果解有效，则该函数返回总值；如果违反约束，则该函数返回零。

def fitness(value: Backpack): Int =
  if(value.canCarryItems && value.areItemsAvailable) value.valueOfItems else 0

Jenetics configuration基因配置

When all of that is ready, I can start configuring the Evolver, which is the class that implements the genetic algorithm in Jenetics.当所有这些都准备好后，我可以开始配置 Evolver，它是在 Jenetics 中实现遗传算法的类。

First, I give it the fitness function and the structure of the genotype. I also tell it that I want to maximize the value of the fitness function and that the population size should be 500. The population is the number of solutions generated in every iteration of the algorithm.首先，我给出了适应度函数和基因型的结构。我还告诉它，我想要最大化适应度函数的值，并且总体大小应该为 500。总体是算法每次迭代中生成的解决方案的数量。

Survivors selection幸存者选择

After that, I define the way to decide which elements of the population are going to survive and be copied to the next iteration. I define the selector function. In this case, a “tournament” function which is a fency name of a function that takes n best solutions (best means, having the highest fitness score).之后，我定义了决定总体中哪些元素将生存并复制到下一次迭代的方法。我定义了选择器函数。在本例中，“锦标赛”函数是一个函数的昵称，该函数采用 n 个最佳解决方案（最佳意味着，具有最高的适应度分数）。

I want 20 survivors, so I set the survivor size and the number of solutions that win the tournament. If I used a smaller number as the tournament parameter the next iteration would contain duplicates of the best solutions from the previous one (it is not necessarily bad, but as the consequence, one genotype may dominate the gene pool).我想要 20 个幸存者，因此我设置了幸存者的大小和赢得比赛的解决方案的数量。如果我使用较小的数字作为锦标赛参数，则下一次迭代将包含上一次迭代中最佳解决方案的重复项（这不一定是坏事，但结果是，一种基因型可能在基因库中占主导地位）。

Offspring selection后代选择

It is a genetic algorithm, so my solutions need to “reproduce.” The offspring selector is used to decide which genotypes will become “parents.”它是一种遗传算法，所以我的解决方案需要“重现”。后代选择器用于决定哪些基因型将成为“父母”。

The roulette wheel is a function which gives a higher chance of reproducing to the solutions which have a higher fitness score. The worse solutions have a lower probability of reproducing but may get lucky and pass their genes to the next generation.轮盘赌轮是一种提供更高机会重现具有较高适应度分数的解决方案的函数。较差的解决方案繁殖的可能性较低，但可能会幸运并将其基因传递给下一代。

Crossover and mutations交叉和突变

In the end, I define the way of combining the “parents” genes. I want to use the crossover method which splits the parents’ genes and takes one part from the first parent and the second part from the other parent. In this case, it is going to be a single point crossover, so the parent gene is split in a one randomly selected position.最后我定义了“父母”基因的结合方式。我想使用交叉方法，将父母的基因分开，一部分来自第一个父母，第二部分来自另一个父母。在这种情况下，这将是单点交叉，因此亲本基因被分裂在一个随机选择的位置。

As the last step, I add the “swap” mutation which randomly swaps parts of the “children’s” genotype. Such a mutation prevents the algorithm from getting stuck in a local maximum, because the mutation may randomly produce a solution which is way better than anything that may be generated by combining the “parent’s” genotypes.作为最后一步，我添加了“交换”突变，随机交换“儿童”基因型的部分内容。这种突变可以防止算法陷入局部最大值，因为突变可能会随机产生一个解决方案，该解决方案比通过组合“父母”基因型生成的任何解决方案都要好。

val evolver = Evolver(fitness, genotype)
    .maximizing()
    .populationSize(500)
    .survivorsSelector(selectors.tournament(20))
    .survivorsSize(20)
    .offspringSelector(selectors.rouletteWheel())
    .geneticOperators(operators.crossover.singlePoint(), operators.mutator.swap())
    .build()

Running the algorithm运行算法

Now, I can run the genetic algorithm (in this example, generate 5000 populations) and see what solution I get.现在，我可以运行遗传算法（在本例中，生成 5000 个群体）并查看得到什么解决方案。

val best = evolver.streamScalaStdLib().drop(5000).head

Console.println(best.bestPhenotype)
Console.println(s"Max weights: ${best.bestPhenotype.head.maxWeightLbs}")
Console.println(s"is not too heavy: ${best.bestPhenotype.head.canCarryItems}")
Console.println(s"is possible: ${best.bestPhenotype.head.areItemsAvailable}")
Console.println(s"Weight: ${best.bestPhenotype.head.weightOfItems}")
Console.println(s"Value: ${best.bestPhenotype.head.valueOfItems}")

Software craft软件工艺

Is programming art or science?编程是艺术还是科学？

On a quest to find the right metaphor寻找正确的隐喻
Bartosz Mikulski 24 Oct 2018 – 3 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 10 月 24 日 – 阅读时间 3 分钟

How do we define programming? Some people adhere to the engineering definition of programming. They talk about building stuff, they call themselves engineers or architects.我们如何定义编程？有些人坚持编程的工程定义。他们谈论建筑，他们称自己为工程师或建筑师。

There are others who focus more on the part of programming that resembles fine art. They talk about elegance, solutions that “feel natural.” There is also a subtle difference in the vocabulary they use. They don’t say “building things,” they talk about “making.”还有一些人更关注类似于美术的编程部分。他们谈论优雅、“感觉自然”的解决方案。他们使用的词汇也有细微的差别。他们不说“建造东西”，而是谈论“制造”。

Art or science?艺术还是科学？

So what is programming? Art or science? Maybe we picked the wrong metaphor. Maybe we should not call software engineering. What if programming is like cooking?那么什么是编程呢？艺术还是科学？也许我们选错了比喻。也许我们不应该称之为软件工程。如果编程就像做饭怎么办？

For sure, there is art in cooking. There is an enormous difference in results achieved by a skilled cook and a novice, even if they follow the same instructions and use the same ingredients. Not only is it essential to follow the recipe, but also it is crucial to pay attention to the visual part of the outcome.毫无疑问，烹饪是有艺术的。即使熟练的厨师和新手遵循相同的说明并使用相同的食材，他们所取得的结果也存在巨大差异。不仅遵循配方很重要，而且关注结果的视觉部分也很重要。

Both results can achieve the simple goal: feeding a person, but we have way more expectations when we talk about food and cooking. In programming, we often want to produce code that not only does everything it should do, but also code that looks good and can be shown to other programmers.这两种结果都可以实现一个简单的目标：养活一个人，但当我们谈论食物和烹饪时，我们有更多的期望。在编程中，我们经常希望生成的代码不仅能完成应做的所有事情，而且代码看起来不错并且可以向其他程序员展示。

There is science in cooking. For sure, you can blindly follow instructions and cook an egg for 7 minutes. You can also dig into the chemistry behind cooking an egg and understand why you should do it and how the cooking time affects the result.烹饪是有科学的。当然，你可以盲目地按照说明煮鸡蛋 7 分钟。您还可以深入研究煮鸡蛋背后的化学原理，了解为什么要这样做以及烹饪时间如何影响结果。

When I cook an egg, the process is straightforward. An egg = 7 minutes. In the end, I get what I wanted, a cooked egg. I know that you can cook it for 5 or 10 minutes and get a different result. That is all I know about cooking eggs.当我煮鸡蛋时，过程很简单。一个鸡蛋=7分钟。最后，我得到了我想要的，一个煮熟的鸡蛋。我知道你可以煮5或10分钟，得到不同的结果。这就是我对煮鸡蛋的全部了解。

You don’t need to understand that to make breakfast. Yet, there are people out there who know that cooked egg is not just one or three outcomes, but a whole spectrum. They can make precisely what they want.你不需要明白这一点就能做早餐。然而，有人知道煮熟的鸡蛋不仅仅是一三个结果，而是一个整体。他们可以精确地制造出他们想要的东西。

The same situation happens in software engineering. For example, you can know the basic algorithms, data structures, the most popular framework, and libraries. That is enough to build software. If you learn more, you can not only develop software but use the most appropriate tool and get precisely the result you want.同样的情况也发生在软件工程中。例如，你可以了解基本的算法、数据结构、最流行的框架和库。这足以构建软件。如果您了解更多，您不仅可以开发软件，还可以使用最合适的工具并准确地获得您想要的结果。

Craft工艺

There is the third part. The part that is not quite an art, not quite science. The process and discipline.还有第三部分。这部分不完全是一门艺术，也不完全是科学。过程和纪律。

We call it software craft. In the kitchen, it is called hygiene.我们称之为软件工艺。在厨房里，这叫卫生。

When we eat out, we hope that the cooks keep their workplace clean. We don’t think about it, but we assume that the ingredients are correctly stored, and raw meat is not prepared in the same place where they make a salad. We even have institutions that make sure the rules are followed and who punish abusers.当我们外出就餐时，我们希望厨师保持工作场所清洁。我们没有考虑这一点，但我们假设原料存储正确，并且生肉不是在制作沙拉的同一个地方准备的。我们甚至设有确保规则得到遵守并惩罚滥用者的机构。

Sometimes we say that the craft is not essential. Well, it is not required in the kitchen either. Often you can ignore those rules, and nothing happens. Sure, you can be lucky. How many times have you eaten something and were… unlucky? The same happens in software.有时我们说手艺不是必需的。嗯，厨房里也不需要它。通常，您可以忽略这些规则，但什么也不会发生。当然，你可能很幸运。有多少次你吃了东西却……不走运？同样的情况也发生在软件领域。

Kitchen?厨房？

So is programming an art, science or engineering? It is all of that at the same time, just like your culinary skills.那么编程是一门艺术、科学还是工程呢？这一切都是同时发生的，就像你的烹饪技巧一样。

Even the entry barrier is similar to cooking. You can cook for yourself, your family and friends without any formal education or training. You don’t need it even if you want to open your own restaurant and prepare food for other people.就连进入门槛也和做饭类似。您可以为自己、家人和朋友做饭，无需接受任何正规教育或培训。即使您想开自己的餐厅并为其他人准备食物，您也不需要它。

Let’s cook something.我们来煮点东西吧。
