Can we make it more generic?我们可以让它更通用吗？

What can we learn from a horrible mistake made by a programmer who wanted to make the code more generic?我们可以从一个想让代码更通用的程序员所犯的可怕错误中学到什么？
Bartosz Mikulski 06 Jun 2018 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 6 月 6 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

I remember many horrible mistakes. I think we can learn a lot from one that looked innocent at the beginning and then turned into a monster.我记得许多可怕的错误。我认为我们可以从一个一开始看起来很无辜，后来变成了一个怪物的人身上学到很多东西。

We had a small function:我们有一个小功能：

getUnfixedErrors()

It searched through the event log, looked for “error” events and then it was looking for “error fixed” events. If it could not find one, we returned the event as an unfixed error.它搜索事件日志，查找“错误”事件，然后查找“错误已修复”事件。如果找不到，我们会将该事件作为未修复的错误返回。

One day we decided that we must make it more generic, because someone may need to use it for different purposes. After all, it was an event log. You can store anything you want, not only errors.有一天，我们决定必须使其更加通用，因为有人可能需要将它用于不同的目的。毕竟，这是一个事件日志。您可以存储任何您想要的内容，而不仅仅是错误。

Because of that, we changed the friendly name of the function to:因此，我们将该函数的友好名称更改为：

getEventsOfTypeWithoutSubsequentEventsOfAnotherType(
    eventType: String, anotherEventType: String
)

First of all, I have to apologize. I am sorry for creating such an abomination. It is wrong on so many levels.首先，我必须道歉。我很抱歉制造了如此令人憎恶的事情。这在很多层面上都是错误的。

The name is extremely long. I used to write very long names. A few years ago, when I was still using Windows XP, I learned about the path length limit because of a long class name. I hit the Windows XP path length limit… repeatedly.名字特别长。我曾经写过很长的名字。几年前，当我还在使用Windows XP时，我因为类名太长而了解到路径长度限制。我多次达到 Windows XP 路径长度限制。

The second problem is the fact that the function is “stringly-typed.” Event types are just strings. If you want to know why I think it is a horrible idea, read this blog post.第二个问题是该函数是“字符串类型”的。事件类型只是字符串。如果您想知道为什么我认为这是一个可怕的想法，请阅读这篇博文。

By changing the function name, we increased cognitive overload. We wanted to make it so generic that we diluted the meaning. It used to be easy to read and understand. The new name of the function makes you think. There is nothing wrong with calling a function “get unfixed errors” if you use it only for that purpose.通过更改函数名称，我们增加了认知过载。我们想让它变得如此通用，以至于淡化了它的含义。它曾经很容易阅读和理解。函数的新名称让你思考。如果您仅将函数用于此目的，则调用函数“获取未修复的错误”并没有什么问题。

We exposed the implementation details in a righteous attempt to increase code reuse. Nobody needs to know if we store errors as events. The sad fact is that we use this function only to find unfixed errors. We don’t even care about other types of events.我们公开了实现细节，以提高代码重用性。没有人需要知道我们是否将错误存储为事件。可悲的事实是，我们使用此函数只是为了查找未修复的错误。我们甚至不关心其他类型的事件。

No reason没有理由

Who wanted the generic version of this function? Nobody! Nobody cares whether the function looks for events without subsequent events of another type. People wanted to use it only to find unfixed errors.谁想要这个函数的通用版本？没有人！没有人关心该函数是否查找没有其他类型后续事件的事件。人们只是想用它来发现未修复的错误。

Let’s face reality. We write generic code to look cool. Abstractions are tools. We like creating tools. We like it because people like us use our tools. Other programmers may appreciate your cleverness. The users never do it. They admire the work done by UX designers.让我们面对现实吧。我们编写通用代码是为了看起来很酷。抽象是工具。我们喜欢创造工具。我们喜欢它，因为像我们这样的人使用我们的工具。其他程序员可能会欣赏你的聪明才智。用户从来不这样做。他们钦佩用户体验设计师所做的工作。

We, the programmers, need to focus on solving the problems we have, not the problem we wish we had. We must not create needless abstractions only because we think they may be useful one day or because we want to brag about the cool library we wrote.我们，程序员，需要专注于解决我们遇到的问题，而不是我们希望遇到的问题。我们不能仅仅因为我们认为有一天它们可能有用或者因为我们想吹嘘我们编写的很酷的库而创建不必要的抽象。

Software engineering软件工程

Assert object pattern断言对象模式

The easiest way to make your tests more readable and easier to maintain使测试更具可读性且更易于维护的最简单方法
Bartosz Mikulski 12 Dec 2018 – 1 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 12 月 12 日 – 阅读 1 分钟

One of the most significant problems with tests written by developers is the fact that such tests do not verify business invariants but the underlying technical details.开发人员编写的测试最重要的问题之一是，此类测试并不验证业务不变性，而是验证底层的技术细节。

When a developer writes a shopping cart part of the application and implements adding an item to the reservation, the test most likely looks like this:当开发人员编写应用程序的购物车部分并实现将项目添加到预订时，测试很可能如下所示：

val reservation = Reservation(...)
val item = Item(...)

reservation.add(item)

reservation.items has size 1
reservation.items.head shouldEqual item
reservation.totalPrice shouldEqual item.price * 1.23

The developer wants to know whether the shopping cart contains the added item, there are no other items in the shopping cart, and whether the VAT tax has been added to the total price of the reservation.开发者想知道购物车中是否包含添加的商品，购物车中没有其他商品，以及预订总价中是否已添加增值税。

What is wrong with that? This code dissects the objects. I look at the code, and all I see are technical details. Where is the meaning?这有什么问题吗？这段代码剖析了对象。我查看代码，看到的都是技术细节。意义在哪里？

Step 1. Hide the assertion步骤 1. 隐藏断言

How can we write such tests better? We can use the Assert Object pattern. It is an object that wraps the result and exposes methods which verify the object’s properties. The most trivial usage of this pattern would look like this:我们怎样才能更好地编写这样的测试呢？我们可以使用断言对象模式。它是一个包装结果并公开验证对象属性的方法的对象。此模式最简单的用法如下所示：

val reservation = Reservation(...)
val item = Item(...)

reservation.add(item)

val assertion = Assert(reservation)
assertion.hasSize(1)
assertion.hasItem(item)
assertion.hasPrice(item.price * 1.23)

It hides the dissecting of the result, but it does not look much better than the previous example.它隐藏了对结果的剖析，但看起来并不比前面的示例好多少。

Step 2. Show the meaning步骤 2. 表达含义

Fortunately, we can fix that. If we invest some time in implementing the assert objects, we can create a nice fluent interface:幸运的是，我们可以解决这个问题。如果我们投入一些时间来实现断言对象，我们可以创建一个漂亮的流畅界面：

val reservation = Reservation(...)
val item = Item(...)

reservation.add(item)

Assert(reservation)
 .hasItem(item)
 .hasNoOtherItems()
 .hasItemPriceWithVATTax(item)

Why is it better? This is the text we had in the Jira ticket. The text that was written in the specification is written in code. The test shows the user’s intent.为什么更好？这是 Jira 票证中的文本。规范中编写的文本是用代码编写的。测试显示了用户的意图。

Why don’t we do it?我们为什么不这样做呢？
We must create such assert objects ourselves. We must write the methods of the fluent interface. Assert objects are not given to us for free. It is much easier to import assertions from a testing library and verify the technical details.我们必须自己创建这样的断言对象。我们必须编写流畅接口的方法。 Assert 对象不是免费提供给我们的。从测试库导入断言并验证技术细节要容易得多。

Software engineering软件工程 TDD时分双工

4 reasons why TDD slows you downTDD 拖慢你速度的 4 个原因

It is easy to announce that TDD slows you down, but have you ever wondered why it happens? Is there anything you can do better?很容易就会宣称 TDD 会降低你的速度，但你有没有想过为什么会发生这种情况？有什么你可以做得更好的吗？
Bartosz Mikulski 08 May 2017 – 4 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2017 年 5 月 8 日 – 阅读 4 分钟

TDD slows you down. I know it does. It was slowing me down too. Don’t you think that it is normal at the beginning of doing something new? The problem is, in the case of TDD, the beginning lasts for a few months. It takes a lot of time before we get used to test-driven development.TDD 会让你放慢速度。我知道确实如此。这也让我放慢了速度。你不觉得刚开始做新事情很正常吗？问题是，对于 TDD，开始会持续几个月。我们需要花费很多时间才能习惯测试驱动开发。

Why test-driven development slows us down? There are four reasons: not enough experience of the programmers, short attention span, misunderstanding of the “unit” word, and lack of fun.为什么测试驱动开发会减慢我们的速度？原因有四个：程序员的经验不够、注意力不够、对“单元”这个词理解错误、缺乏乐趣。

Not enough experience经验不足

The obvious reason. It is not sufficient to read a book and a few articles. You need to practice at work or while working on side projects. Practicing on toy examples is good on the first day, later it is just a waste of your time.显而易见的原因。读一本书和几篇文章是不够的。您需要在工作中或在从事业余项目时进行练习。第一天练习玩具示例很好，但到了后面就只是浪费时间了。

I know you don’t have time. You are probably reading this blog post on your mobile phone while waiting for something or someone. If you need more time, make some time. There are millions of articles about time management. You can read one or two while standing in a line.我知道你没有时间。您可能在等待某事或某人时正在手机上阅读这篇博文。如果您需要更多时间，请腾出一些时间。关于时间管理的文章有数百万篇。您可以在排队时阅读一两本。

There is one good excuse. You can tell that you prefer to spend time with your children. That is awesome. Would you like to become their role model? You can not only nag them to read a book or do their homework, but also show them that you do it: “Learning is important, even adults learn every day!”有一个很好的借口。您可以看出您更喜欢与孩子共度时光。太棒了。你想成为他们的榜样吗？你不仅可以唠叨他们看书或做作业，还可以向他们表明你做到了：“学习很重要，即使是成年人也每天都在学习！”

Short attention span注意力持续时间短

You start implementing something and think that it is an excellent opportunity to practice TDD. You think about the first test. Then you write your first failing test. Write a little bit of code, run the test, see that it passes. After that, you refactor the code. What should you do now?你开始实施一些东西，并认为这是练习 TDD 的绝佳机会。你想想第一个测试。然后你编写第一个失败的测试。编写一点代码，运行测试，看看它是否通过。之后，您重构代码。你现在应该做什么？

Do you even remember? Now you have to switch back and forth between your code, tests, and task description. Do you know which test you should write right now? No?你还记得吗？现在您必须在代码、测试和任务描述之间来回切换。您知道现在应该写哪个测试吗？不？

Make a list of all the tests you need before you start writing. Yes, you are actually going to plan something. You can even think about design. Yes, it is allowed.在开始写作之前，列出您需要的所有测试。是的，你实际上要计划一些事情。你甚至可以考虑设计。是的，这是允许的。

You can paste the list of necessary tests into your code as a comment. Please remember about removing it after you finish. If you think you need an additional test, add it to the list. Just keep everything in one place.您可以将必要的测试列表作为注释粘贴到代码中。请记住在完成后将其删除。如果您认为需要额外的测试，请将其添加到列表中。只需将所有内容放在一处即可。

You misunderstood the word “unit”你对“单位”这个词有什么误解

Every time we speak about TDD, someone mentions unit tests. If you think that a unit test is a test that verifies one method or a function, do not even start test-driven development. It will slow you down.每次我们谈论 TDD 时，都会有人提到单元测试。如果您认为单元测试是验证一种方法或功能的测试，那么甚至不要开始测试驱动开发。它会让你放慢速度。

When you write tests for every function/method, you probably stub/mock every dependency. What is going to happen when you want to refactor your code? You need to change many tests! It will take a lot of time, and you will scream about tests slowing you down!当您为每个函数/方法编写测试时，您可能会存根/模拟每个依赖项。当您想重构代码时会发生什么？你需要改变很多测试！这会花费很多时间，而且你会尖叫着测试让你放慢了速度！

Let me make a bold statement: every time you stub/mock code which is not used to communicate with an external dependency (database, REST service, file system, etc.) you are doing something wrong.让我大胆声明一下：每次你对不用于与外部依赖项（数据库、REST 服务、文件系统等）进行通信的存根/模拟代码进行操作时，你都在做错事。

Your tests should test the observable behavior, the expected result, the fact that something has been stored in the database, or a message has been sent.您的测试应该测试可观察的行为、预期结果、数据库中已存储某些内容或已发送消息的事实。

It is not fun这并不好玩

You know what is not fun? Receiving the same bug report four times. Spending three hours debugging 43 if-else statements in a very long file.你知道什么不好玩吗？四次收到相同的错误报告。花了三个小时调试一个很长的文件中的 43 个 if-else 语句。

Sometimes failure is part of the fun. You try something, fail, try again, fail, learn something new, and try a dozen times more. Occasionally, I can enjoy failure, but at the end of the day, I don’t want to be depressed because I haven’t finished any of my tasks.有时失败也是乐趣的一部分。你尝试某件事，失败，再尝试，失败，学习新东西，然后再尝试十几次。偶尔，我可以享受失败，但最终，我不想因为没有完成任何任务而感到沮丧。

In fact, when you are proficient in TDD, it becomes fun. It is like checking off items on your TODO list, one test at a time. You feel incredibly motivated.事实上，当你精通TDD时，它就变得很有趣。这就像检查待办事项清单上的项目，一次一项测试。你会感到无比的动力。

Excuses借口

I know, now you are thinking about a bunch of work-related excuses. There must be an external factor that doesn’t allow you to practice TDD.我知道，现在你正在考虑一堆与工作有关的借口。一定有外部因素不允许你练习TDD。

My boss won’t let me do it我的老板不让我这样做

If your boss doesn’t want to give you enough time to do your job correctly and he/she is outraged when someone finds a bug in your software, then I feel sorry for you. Unfortunately, I cannot help you.如果你的老板不想给你足够的时间来正确地完成你的工作，并且当有人在你的软件中发现错误时他/她感到愤怒，那么我为你感到难过。不幸的是，我无法帮助你。

On the other hand, your boss may forbid you to “waste” time on TDD and also doesn’t care about the quality of your work. If it is the case, feel free to continue whatever you are doing. I hope I don’t use your products.另一方面，你的老板可能会禁止你在 TDD 上“浪费”时间，而且也不关心你的工作质量。如果是这样，请随意继续您正在做的事情。我希望我不要使用你们的产品。

I work with legacy code我使用遗留代码

There is a great book about it: “Working Effectively with Legacy Code” by Michael Feathers. Read it. Right now.有一本关于它的好书：Michael Feathers 的《有效处理遗留代码》。阅读。现在。

Learning学习

Practicing TDD is like learning to read. It will take a lot of time. In the beginning, you will be terrible at doing it.练习 TDD 就像学习阅读一样。这将需要很多时间。一开始，你会很难做到这一点。

TDD时分双工 Data Engineering数据工程

Testing legacy data pipelines测试遗留数据管道

Do you struggle with maintaining your legacy data pipelines? Check out our article on how to add tests and refactor your code while working with legacy data pipelines.您是否在维护遗留数据管道方面遇到困难？查看我们的文章，了解如何在使用遗留数据管道时添加测试和重构代码。
Bartosz Mikulski 21 Jan 2022 – 6 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2022 年 1 月 21 日 – 阅读 6 分钟

Have you ever seen a team afraid of a data pipeline? The code constantly fails in production. They have to spend hours restarting the tasks and copying the data between locations to make it work. However, they never attempt to fix the underlying problem.您见过有团队害怕数据管道吗？该代码在生产中不断失败。他们必须花费数小时重新启动任务并在位置之间复制数据才能使其正常工作。然而，他们从不尝试解决根本问题。

“You don’t touch that code,” they say, “every time we want to fix it, everything becomes even worse.”“你不要碰那些代码，”他们说，“每次我们想要修复它时，一切都会变得更糟。”

Can we do anything about such data pipelines?我们能对这样的数据管道做些什么吗？

How to understand and fix old code如何理解和修复旧代码

Let’s be honest here. You will need to refactor the code. You will need to change its structure to reveal the intent and makes it easier to understand and modify.让我们说实话。您将需要重构代码。您将需要更改其结构以揭示意图并使其更易于理解和修改。

Working with messy code resembles cooking at home without having a proper kitchen. If your cooker is in one room, the only sink in the house in another one, you keep the food in the fridge standing in the basement, and your cooking utensils are all over the place, you will burn all the food (and maybe the house too) while running around to find what you need. Clean up the mess first.使用凌乱的代码就像在没有合适厨房的情况下在家做饭一样。如果你的炊具在一个房间里，房子里唯一的水槽在另一个房间里，你把冰箱里的食物放在地下室里，你的炊具到处都是，你会烧掉所有的食物（也许还有房子也一样），同时四处寻找你需要的东西。先把烂摊子收拾干净。

Unfortunately, refactoring the code isn’t as easy as collecting all of the pieces together and putting them in one place. It wouldn’t work. We need to ensure we don’t change the code’s behavior while refactoring.不幸的是，重构代码并不像将所有部分收集在一起并将它们放在一个地方那么容易。这是行不通的。我们需要确保重构时不会改变代码的行为。

How do we do it? We need automated tests. That’s the only way.我们该怎么做呢？我们需要自动化测试。这是唯一的方法。

Adding tests to the legacy code向遗留代码添加测试

How do we add tests to existing code? It shouldn’t be a problem because many developers do it all the time. First, they write the code. Later, they write the tests for the code they had just written.我们如何向现有代码添加测试？这应该不是问题，因为许多开发人员一直这样做。首先，他们编写代码。随后，他们为刚刚编写的代码编写测试。

However, this time we had one minor complication. Someone else wrote the code months or years ago. What do we do now?然而，这次我们遇到了一个小并发症。其他人在几个月或几年前编写了代码。我们现在干什么？

Start testing in the worst part of the code从代码中最糟糕的部分开始测试

To see the benefits of your effort fast and get the largest return-on-investment possible, we must begin our efforts in the worst part of the code.为了快速看到您的努力的好处并获得尽可能最大的投资回报，我们必须从代码中最糟糕的部分开始我们的努力。

What is the worst? I assume you know which part breaks most often. That’s the place where we must start.最糟糕的是什么？我假设您知道哪个部分最常损坏。这就是我们必须开始的地方。

However, our task may differ slightly depending on the part of the code causing the problems. Is this the data loading code? In this case, we will test the data validation code (assuming it exists) because, in the long run, we need to improve the mechanism filtering out invalid data. Is the processing pipeline breaking in the middle of the transformation because of nulls? Some earlier actions caused the problem. Look for the part producing those nulls and start testing there.但是，根据导致问题的代码部分，我们的任务可能会略有不同。这是数据加载代码吗？在这种情况下，我们将测试数据验证代码（假设它存在），因为从长远来看，我们需要改进过滤无效数据的机制。处理管道是否因空值而在转换过程中中断？一些早期的操作导致了这个问题。寻找产生这些空值的部分并开始在那里进行测试。

Locate the troublemaking code and write tests for its current behavior. It’s crucial to test the current behavior! We don’t change it yet. It may be wrong, but we must preserve it. At least for a while.找到引发问题的代码并为其当前行为编写测试。测试当前的行为至关重要！我们还没有改变它。它可能是错误的，但我们必须保留它。至少有一段时间。

Cleaning the mess清理混乱

I recommend extracting the code you want to change to a separate class or module. After extracting the code and adding the tests, you have a decently tested module you can refactor.我建议将您想要更改的代码提取到单独的类或模块中。提取代码并添加测试后，您就有了一个经过适当测试的可以重构的模块。

It’s not the time to fix the bugs yet! Our goal now is to make the code easy to understand. We can rename variables or extract functions and classes. Do whatever you have to do to make it easy to work with.现在还不是修复错误的时候！我们现在的目标是使代码易于理解。我们可以重命名变量或提取函数和类。尽一切努力让工作变得轻松。

Fixing the problems解决问题

You have probably noticed a bunch of errors in the code already. Some problems became apparent when you removed the mess hiding the issue. Great! Now, we can start fixing it.您可能已经注意到代码中存在一堆错误。当您消除隐藏问题的混乱时，一些问题就变得明显了。伟大的！现在，我们可以开始修复它了。

How do we do it? First, we make sure we have a test for the current behavior of the code. The test must pass.我们该怎么做呢？首先，我们确保对代码的当前行为进行测试。测试必须通过。

After that, we write a new test for the expected behavior. At this point, you can mark the old test as ignored or remove it already. You may want to look at the old test code, but we won’t run it anymore. Whatever you do, remember to remove the old test when you finish.之后，我们为预期行为编写一个新的测试。此时，您可以将旧测试标记为忽略或将其删除。您可能想查看旧的测试代码，但我们不会再运行它。无论您做什么，请记住在完成后删除旧的测试。

With a new failing test, we can start the red-green-refactor cycle just like any new code. At this stage, we are in the familiar, friendly environment of TDD again.通过新的失败测试，​​我们可以像任何新代码一样开始红绿重构循环。这个阶段，我们又回到了熟悉的、友好的TDD环境中。

Should you care about test coverage?您应该关心测试覆盖率吗？

Test coverage is a useless metric at every stage of every project.在每个项目的每个阶段，测试覆盖率都是一个无用的指标。

The code coverage doesn’t tell you whether the programmer has written the tests correctly or whether the author overmocked all dependencies, wrote a test for every method, and repeated the same logic in the tests and the code.代码覆盖率并不能告诉您程序员是否正确编写了测试，或者作者是否过度模拟了所有依赖项，为每个方法编写了测试，并在测试和代码中重复了相同的逻辑。

We want to test every branch of the behavior, not every code branch. Of course, testing all of the behavior will test all of the code. However, when we write those tests, we want to look at a higher level of abstraction.我们想要测试行为的每个分支，而不是每个代码分支。当然，测试所有行为也就测试了所有代码。然而，当我们编写这些测试时，我们想要查看更高层次的抽象。

Testing every function separately is a waste of time. The behavior (and all the bugs) is hidden in the interactions between the parts of the code. We should test that.单独测试每个功能是浪费时间。行为（以及所有错误）隐藏在代码各部分之间的交互中。我们应该测试一下。

There is no metric telling us whether we tested all code behaviors. Because of that, we shouldn’t worry too much about test coverage.没有任何指标可以告诉我们是否测试了所有代码行为。正因为如此，我们不应该太担心测试覆盖率。

Protect the data!保护数据！

All your efforts are futile if you don’t ensure the correctness of the output data.如果不能保证输出数据的正确性，你的所有努力都是徒劳的。

In data engineering, that’s our only goal. Without it, everything else makes no sense.在数据工程中，这是我们唯一的目标。没有它，其他一切都没有意义。

The best time investment you can make is testing the incoming data and ensuring data quality before running any data transformations. Because of that, I suggest starting your testing and refactoring efforts with the data validation code. After all, the garbage-in garbage-out rule applies to all data pipelines.您可以做出的最佳时间投资是在运行任何数据转换之前测试传入数据并确保数据质量。因此，我建议从数据验证代码开始测试和重构工作。毕竟，垃圾进垃圾出规则适用于所有数据管道。

When you finish with data validation, I suggest switching to testing the output of the entire pipeline. In short, you validate whether your results are correct. We don’t want to propagate the mess downstream, do we? We don’t need untrustworthy data in the data lake.当您完成数据验证后，我建议切换到测试整个管道的输出。简而言之，您验证您的结果是否正确。我们不想将混乱传播到下游，不是吗？我们不需要数据湖中不可信的数据。

In the end, we can deal with the data transformation logic. There is a catch; however, what if the output is wrong because of an error at an earlier stage? In such a case, we write the tests for the output first, then we test the problematic part of the code and start fixing the root cause of the issue.最后，我们可以处理数据转换逻辑。有一个问题；但是，如果由于前期的错误导致输出错误怎么办？在这种情况下，我们首先编写输出测试，然后测试代码中有问题的部分并开始修复问题的根本原因。

We make small steps towards the root cause at every stage, and we add tests along the way. That’s the only rule for working with untested data pipelines.我们在每个阶段都朝着根本原因迈出一小步，并在此过程中添加测试。这是使用未经测试的数据管道的唯一规则。

What kind of testing?什么样的测试？

When discussing software testing, we usually must clarify what kind of tests we expect. Do we write unit tests? What is a unit anyway?在讨论软件测试时，我们通常必须明确我们期望什么样的测试。我们编写单元测试吗？单位到底是什么？

We don’t need to name the tests. Programmers want to work with unified structures, and we tend to put things into distinct categories making up arbitrary rules about differences between those categories. However, data engineers should feel good working with unstructured data. We may have unstructured tests too.我们不需要为测试命名。程序员希望使用统一的结构，并且我们倾向于将事物放入不同的类别中，从而对这些类别之间的差异制定任意规则。然而，数据工程师应该对处理非结构化数据感到满意。我们也可能有非结构化测试。

The goal is to test the business logic and get the high-quality data to the data warehouse or the data lake as fast as possible. If we succeed, the kind of tests we write won’t matter.目标是测试业务逻辑并尽快将高质量的数据获取到数据仓库或数据湖。如果我们成功了，我们编写的测试类型就不重要了。

Nevertheless, I have a suggestion about testing data pipelines. What seems to work well is a testing method based on behavior-driven development. It works because you must describe the business logic in a human-readable language, so you may spot inconsistencies or get the logic validated by a subject matter expert.尽管如此，我对测试数据管道有一个建议。看起来效果很好的是基于行为驱动开发的测试方法。它之所以有效，是因为您必须以人类可读的语言描述业务逻辑，因此您可能会发现不一致之处或让主题专家验证逻辑。

Software Craft软件工艺 TDD时分双工

Why should you practice TDD?为什么要练习 TDD？

What are the benefits of TDD for programmers and companies that hire them?TDD 对于程序员和雇佣他们的公司有什么好处？
Bartosz Mikulski 30 Sep 2022 – 7 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2022 年 9 月 30 日 – 阅读 7 分钟

In 2014, J. B. Rainsberger wrote, “I started practicing test-driven development because I saw that my job was draining my energy and taking up too much time.” Should you practice TDD for the same reason?2014 年，J. B. Rainsberger 写道：“我开始练习测试驱动开发，因为我发现我的工作耗尽了我的精力并占用了太多时间。”出于同样的原因，你应该练习 TDD 吗？

Does TDD require less energy than manual testing and debugging?TDD 是否比手动测试和调试需要更少的精力？

How can TDD require less energy if you are supposed to make more effort? You not only have to write the code, but you also need the tests. You need the tests before you write the code, so you have to know what you will write before writing it. Those are three actions instead of one! It looks like more effort, but it isn’t.如果你应该付出更多的努力，TDD 又怎么会需要更少的精力呢？您不仅需要编写代码，还需要测试。在编写代码之前需要进行测试，因此在编写代码之前必须知道要编写什么。这是三个动作而不是一个！看起来需要更多努力，但事实并非如此。

When you practice TDD, you put all your effort into thinking of the next step required to implement the code change. The tests are a consequence of your thinking. Tests require no mental effort when you already know what you expect. After writing the test, you implement the code. Does this require any mental effort? Not really. A proper test diminishes the required effort because you have an external mechanism checking your code. You don’t need to wonder, “Will it work?” You can check it. After implementing code comes refactoring. Does this require lots of effort? A little bit, but not much. Why? Because you can do all the refactoring in small steps while automatically checking whether your code still works.当您练习 TDD 时，您会全力以赴地思考实施代码更改所需的下一步。测试是你思考的结果。当您已经知道自己的期望时，测试不需要费力。编写测试后，您将实现代码。这需要什么脑力劳动吗？并不真地。正确的测试可以减少所需的工作量，因为您有一个外部机制来检查您的代码。你不需要想知道“它会起作用吗？”你可以检查一下。实现代码之后就是重构。这需要很多努力吗？有一点点，但不多。为什么？因为您可以小步完成所有重构，同时自动检查代码是否仍然有效。

What’s the alternative? Manual testing, debugging, and adding useless tests at the end to have “code coverage.” Does it require more energy? We don’t know. It’s unpredictable. You may have all the skills and luck needed to get the code right on the first attempt. If you don’t, you may spend a week fiddling and debugging the code.还有什么选择呢？手动测试、调试并在最后添加无用的测试以获得“代码覆盖率”。它需要更多的能量吗？我们不知道。这是不可预测的。您可能具备在第一次尝试时就获得正确代码所需的所有技能和运气。如果不这样做，您可能会花一周的时间摆弄和调试代码。

Is TDD predictable? No. But it’s more predictable than the write first, test later approach. In TDD, you may spend 30 seconds thinking of your next step, or you may need an entire day. Sometimes it feels like the existing code fights back against any attempt to do TDD. When you work in such a codebase, you will need more time to plan your next steps. Steps! Even though you tackle the problem one step at a time, having a general idea of where you are going does pay off.TDD 是可预测的吗？不。但它比先写、后测试的方法更可预测。在 TDD 中，您可能会花 30 秒思考下一步，也可能需要一整天。有时感觉现有代码会抵制任何 TDD 尝试。当您在这样的代码库中工作时，您将需要更多时间来计划下一步。脚步！即使你一次一步地解决问题，对你的前进方向有一个总体的了解也确实会有回报。

Does TDD make you faster?TDD 会让你更快吗？

In a messy code, the write first, test later people will start coding sooner than a TDD-er. It happens because they are thinking of the solution while they are coding. A TDD-er does most of the thinking before they start typing. The write first, test later programmers may occasionally get lucky and finish the task quickly. But TDD gives you a consistent pace. Your process doesn’t depend on luck. You make stable progress.在混乱的代码中，先编写、后测试的人会比 TDD 更早开始编码。发生这种情况是因为他们在编码时正在考虑解决方案。 TDD 使用者在开始打字之前会进行大部分思考。先写、后测试的程序员有时可能会幸运地快速完成任务。但 TDD 可以让您保持一致的节奏。你的过程并不取决于运气。你取得了稳定的进步。

However, in the beginning, TDD is painful and slow. It’s ok. It’s normal. You are doing something new. Do you have a driving license? If yes, recall the first driving lesson you had. Were you driving with confidence at the maximal allowed speed? Perhaps, a handful of people did. Although, the majority was freaking out and trying not to crash into something.然而，一开始，TDD 是痛苦且缓慢的。没关系。这是正常的。你正在做一些新的事情。你有驾驶执照吗？如果是，请回忆一下您上的第一堂驾驶课。您是否以最大允许速度自信地驾驶？也许，有一小部分人做到了。尽管如此，大多数人还是吓坏了，试图不撞到什么东西。

Test-driven development requires practice. You won’t learn TDD in a week or even a month. You will need months of effort every working day. It seems to be a huge sacrifice, but it’s an investment. Once you learn it, you will get the benefits of the process every day for the rest of your career.测试驱动开发需要实践。你不会在一周甚至一个月内学会 TDD。每个工作日你都需要几个月的努力。这看起来是一个巨大的牺牲，但却是一种投资。一旦你学会了它，你就会在余下的职业生涯中每天从这个过程中获益。

Why should you care about spending less time and having more energy?为什么你应该关心花更少的时间和拥有更多的精力？

Why should you care? You have an employment agreement stating you get paid X for Y working hours. You get the money no matter what. You must show up and make a minimal effort to avoid looking like a slacker. Nothing else is required. Really. Often, people who struggle to get the code right look like someone who works hard, not someone who is incompetent. Why would you like to get the job done faster? It benefits your employer but doesn’t benefit you. Right?你为什么要关心？您有一份雇佣协议，规定您在 Y 工作时间内获得 X 报酬。不管怎样你都能拿到钱。你必须出现并做出最小的努力，以避免看起来像个懒鬼。不需要其他任何东西。真的。通常，那些努力编写正确代码的人看起来像是一个努力工作的人，而不是一个无能的人。为什么你想更快地完成工作？它对你的雇主有利，但对你没有好处。正确的？

That’s only one point of view on the situation. When you agree to trade Y hours for X money, you are supposed to spend those Y hours on something that benefits your employer. But nobody forbids you to spend time on something beneficial for your employer and you!这只是对这种情况的一种观点。当您同意用 Y 小时换取 X 钱时，您应该将这 Y 小时花在对您的雇主有利的事情上。但没有人禁止您花时间做对您的雇主和您都有利的事情！

What should you do? Do something to improve your chances of getting promoted or getting a better job in the future. It’s ok as long as you improve the situation at your current company too! What may you choose?你该怎么办？做一些事情来提高你未来升职或找到更好工作的机会。只要你把现在公司的情况也改善一下就可以了！你可以选择什么？

You can learn another programming language or a new framework. Picking another programming language is the easiest choice for a programmer. But would it make a difference? I can write production backend code in Java, Scala, and Python. I know a little bit of JavaScript and React. Does it make sense to learn Rust or Go? I don’t think so. If I knew only one language, then I would learn another one. The benefits of learning yet another programming language diminish fast. I see no difference between a programmer who knows 3 or 8 languages. The person who knows three may be a better programmer if they spend time learning the details of the standard library in those languages.您可以学习另一种编程语言或新框架。对于程序员来说，选择另一种编程语言是最简单的选择。但这会有什么不同吗？我可以用 Java、Scala 和 Python 编写生产后端代码。我了解一点 JavaScript 和 React。学习 Rust 或 Go 有意义吗？我不这么认为。如果我只懂一种语言，那么我就会学习另一种语言。学习另一种编程语言的好处很快就会消失。我认为懂 3 种或 8 种语言的程序员之间没有什么区别。懂得这三种语言的人如果花时间学习这些语言的标准库的细节，可能会成为更好的程序员。

If not a programming language, then what? If I didn’t know how to train machine learning models, I would learn ML. What’s next? If I didn’t know how to make an ugly front-end, I would learn a front-end framework. Do I want to learn how to implement a beautiful front-end? No. I have no interest in learning design right now.如果不是编程语言，那又是什么？如果我不知道如何训练机器学习模型，我就会学习机器学习。下一步是什么？如果我不知道如何做一个丑陋的前端，我就会学习一个前端框架。我想学习如何实现一个漂亮的前端吗？不，我现在对学习设计没有兴趣。

It’s not only about programming languages. It’s the same story with frameworks and libraries. How many Java dependency injection frameworks do you need to know? One or two. It makes no sense to learn how to use seven of them. What about machine learning? I know how to use Tensorflow with Keras. Will I learn Pytorch? No. It won’t give me any benefits.这不仅仅与编程语言有关。框架和库也是如此。你需要了解多少个Java依赖注入框架？一个或两个。学习如何使用其中七个是没有意义的。机器学习呢？我知道如何将 Tensorflow 与 Keras 结合使用。我会学习 Pytorch 吗？不，它不会给我带来任何好处。

If you are a Java backend developer who knows the Spring framework, pick something that makes you more than a Java backend developer who knows Spring. You have two options: backend and something or backend specializing in something. To get the best results, you should alternate. One time you specialize. The other time, you learn something completely new.如果您是一名了解 Spring 框架的 Java 后端开发人员，请选择一些能让您比了解 Spring 的 Java 后端开发人员更深入的东西。你有两个选择：后端和某些东西或后端专门从事某些东西。为了获得最佳效果，您应该交替进行。一次你专一。另一次，你会学到一些全新的东西。

Right now, I decided to learn marketing. It will be handy when I have to promote myself and my work. Also, I will need marketing if I ever create my software product. After all, most software startups die because everyone wants to write code, and nobody does marketing. How does it benefit my current employer? I hope to learn how we can promote my team’s work better within the company. Usually, data teams are overlooked because we are “the backend of a backend.” With the right marketing skills, we should be able to get more attention.现在，我决定学习营销。当我必须推销自己和我的工作时，它会很方便。另外，如果我创建我的软件产品，我将需要营销。毕竟，大多数软件初创公司的消亡是因为每个人都想编写代码，而没有人做营销。它对我现在的雇主有什么好处？我希望了解如何在公司内更好地促进我的团队的工作。通常，数据团队会被忽视，因为我们是“后端的后端”。有了正确的营销技巧，我们应该能够获得更多的关注。

Why should you promote your work? Because programming is business (even when you are employed). In business, you don’t get participation trophies. No matter where you are in the hierarchy, a higher level has a limited number of seats. Tenure alone can get you to the senior level. If you want anything more, you will need to be seen and positively perceived by those higher in the hierarchy.为什么要推广你的工作？因为编程是生意（即使你有工作）。在商业领域，你不会获得参与奖杯。无论您处于层级中的哪个位置，较高级别的席位数量都是有限的。仅终身教职就可以让你达到高级水平。如果你想要更多，你需要被高层的人看到并积极地看待。

What will the other team members think about it?其他团队成员会怎么想？

If you are on the right team, they will be happy. They are already doing it too.如果你在正确的团队中，他们会很高兴。他们也已经在这样做了。

On the other hand, you may be on a team that opposes everyone who tries to become more than average. What does it look like? It may be a casual comment. A few years ago, I participated in a conversation about video games when I mentioned I was going to buy a gaming console. One person said, “Finally, you will stop blogging.” Apparently, my blog bugged them. Did I stop blogging? No.另一方面，你所在的团队可能反对所有试图超越平均水平的人。它是什么样子的？这可能是一个随意的评论。几年前，我参加了一次有关视频游戏的对话，当时我提到我要购买一台游戏机。一个人说：“你终于要停止写博客了。”显然，我的博客打扰了他们。我停止写博客了吗？不。

Don’t waste your time thinking of people who oppose your growth. They don’t matter.不要浪费时间去想那些反对你成长的人。它们并不重要。

TDD时分双工

How to teach your team to write automated tests?如何教您的团队编写自动化测试？

How to teach writing automated tests: TDD, BDD, and other techniques如何教授编写自动化测试：TDD、BDD 和其他技术
Bartosz Mikulski 24 Sep 2021 – 5 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2021 年 9 月 24 日 – 阅读 5 分钟

Are you a CTO at a startup, a tech lead, or a senior engineer on a team full of people who see tests as a needless burden? Are you tired of seeing them debugging the code for hours when you know that two or three tests written before writing the code would prevent the problem? Do you want to teach them how to write proper tests?您是初创公司的首席技术官、技术主管，还是团队中的高级工程师，而团队中的人都认为测试是不必要的负担？当您知道在编写代码之前编写两到三个测试可以防止问题时，您是否厌倦了看到他们调试代码几个小时？您想教他们如何编写正确的测试吗？

Good. I’m teaching BDD workshops, testing workshops for data engineers, and organizing Software Craft Meetups. Let me tell you what I have learned about teaching people how to write tests.好的。我正在教授 BDD 研讨会、数据工程师测试研讨会以及组织软件工艺聚会。让我告诉你我在教人们如何编写测试方面学到了什么。

Don’t Call it Test-Driven Development不要称之为测试驱动开发

For some reason, people are allergic to the term Test-Driven Development. It happens for many reasons.由于某种原因，人们对“测试驱动开发”这个术语过敏。发生这种情况的原因有很多。

Some loathe the most vocal proponent of TDD - Uncle B. Fortunately, there are others: J. B. Rainsberger, Kent Beck, Anna Filina, Sandro Mancuso, and others. You can pick a role model without significant character flaws.有些人讨厌 TDD 最直言不讳的支持者 - Uncle B。幸运的是，还有其他人：J. B. Rainsberger、Kent Beck、Anna Filina、Sandro Mancuso 等。你可以选择一个没有明显性格缺陷的榜样。

Some people point out that TDD is a design technique, not a way to write automated tests. Right. Tests are just a side effect of TDD. That’s correct, but we still end up with tests. For me, it doesn’t matter how you write the tests, as long as you have them and they are written correctly. In this case, “correctly” means avoiding overmocking and having a correct understanding of the term “unit test.” It is not a test for a single function/method! We are supposed to test a unit of behavior and be able to run the tests independently.有些人指出 TDD 是一种设计技术，而不是一种编写自动化测试的方法。正确的。测试只是 TDD 的副作用。这是正确的，但我们最终还是要进行测试。对我来说，如何编写测试并不重要，只要有测试并且编写正确即可。在这种情况下，“正确”意味着避免过度模拟并正确理解术语“单元测试”。它不是对单个函数/方法的测试！我们应该测试一个行为单元并能够独立运行测试。

Some unfortunate people worked with TDD gatekeepers who told them they were not worthy of calling themselves programmers unless they followed the TDD steps to the letter. I don’t know how you can help those people overcome their TDD trauma.一些不幸的人与 TDD 看门人一起工作，他们告诉他们，除非严格遵循 TDD 步骤，否则不配称自己为程序员。我不知道如何帮助这些人克服 TDD 创伤。

The term TDD may bring lots of negativity. I mention TDD as just one of the options. I prefer names such as “test-first” or just automated code testing. After all, I am here to help those people, not scare them off.TDD 这个词可能会带来很多负面影响。我提到 TDD 只是其中一种选择。我更喜欢诸如“测试优先”或只是自动化代码测试之类的名称。毕竟，我是来帮助那些人的，而不是吓跑他们的。

Don’t Pretend They Won’t Need to Work Hard不要假装他们不需要努力工作

Some people attend the workshops passively. They listen to what I say, they look at the screen when I show them how to write something, but they don’t do any exercises. They sit and wait until the time passes.有些人被动地参加研讨会。他们听我说的话，当我向他们展示如何写东西时他们看着屏幕，但他们不做任何练习。他们坐下来等待时间过去。

Usually, I say multiple times during the workshop that we came here to do exercises because they can watch someone else coding on YouTube. For free. Some people leave when I say it. It is fine. The workshop is an opportunity to practice the skills in a safe environment. You can’t break anything. You won’t get stuck because I am there to answer the questions. All you need is a willingness to do the exercises.通常，我在研讨会期间多次说过我们来这里是为了做练习，因为他们可以在 YouTube 上观看其他人编码。免费。当我说完之后，有些人就离开了。没事。该研讨会是在安全环境中练习技能的机会。你不能破坏任何东西。你不会被困住，因为我会在那里回答问题。您所需要的只是愿意进行练习。

If you teach people how to write tests, you will have similar problems. Some attendees will sit and wait until you magically upload the knowledge into their brains. The sooner you tell them it won’t happen, the better. They may leave when you do it. You may feel bad about people leaving your workshop. I see it differently. If people who want to sit for eight hours leave, I have more time and energy to focus on attendees who want to learn. Those who left can watch the recording later. Of course, they won’t do it, but they can.如果你教人们如何编写测试，你也会遇到类似的问题。有些与会者会坐下来等待，直到您神奇地将知识上传到他们的大脑中。你越早告诉他们这不会发生越好。当你这样做时他们可能会离开。您可能会对人们离开您的工作室感到难过。我有不同的看法。如果想要坐八小时的人离开，我就有更多的时间和精力专注于想要学习的与会者。离开的人可以稍后观看录音。当然，他们不会这么做，但他们可以。

I had workshops where people told me, “You know, we are not doing the exercieses. Just show us how to do it, we will practice later when we watch the recording.” It is a lie. They won’t do the exercises later. They won’t even watch the video.在我举办的研讨会上，人们告诉我，“你知道，我们没有做练习。只要告诉我们怎么做，我们稍后看录音时就会练习。”这是一个谎言。他们以后不会做练习。他们甚至不会看视频。

Nevertheless, I obliged, and I was glad they told me that. We could waste hours if they pretended they were doing the exercises (it was an online workshop, I couldn’t see them). If they didn’t tell me, I would wait 10 minutes, repeatedly asking if anyone had questions or issues with the exercise. Then I would ask who wants to share their solution with the group. Nobody would volunteer. I would write the answer myself. Show them another exercise, explain it, and repeat the process until “we” finish all tasks. I was happy they were brave enough to admit they came to watch someone coding. That saved us hours. I would be happier if they practices, but I have no control over their choices. Neither do you, even if you teach your employees.尽管如此，我还是答应了，我很高兴他们告诉我这一点。如果他们假装正在做练习，我们可能会浪费几个小时（这是一个在线研讨会，我看不到他们）。如果他们不告诉我，我会等 10 分钟，反复询问是否有人对练习有疑问或问题。然后我会问谁愿意与小组分享他们的解决方案。没有人愿意自愿。我会自己写答案。向他们展示另一个练习，解释它，然后重复这个过程，直到“我们”完成所有任务。我很高兴他们有足够的勇气承认他们是来观看某人编码的。这节省了我们几个小时。如果他们练习的话我会更高兴，但我无法控制他们的选择。即使你教导你的员工，你也不会。

You Can’t Teach it你无法教它

This brings us to the last point. You can’t teach automated testing. You can show the proper techniques, give some hints, but in the end, they have to do it themselves. It is like learning a new (human) language. You can sit in a classroom all day long listening to a teacher. You can even do the exercises during the lessons and all of the homework. But that won’t be enough until you attempt to use the language in a real conversation when you have half of a second to think about what you want to say and how to say it correctly.这引出了最后一点。你无法教授自动化测试。你可以展示正确的技巧，给出一些提示，但最终，他们必须自己做。这就像学习一门新的（人类）语言。你可以整天坐在教室里听老师讲课。您甚至可以在课程和所有作业期间进行练习。但这还不够，除非你尝试在真正的对话中使用该语言，并且你有半秒钟的时间来思考你想说的内容以及如何正确地说出来。

Practicing during a workshop is just a starting point. Signing up is not enough. Paying for the workshop is not enough. Even attending and sitting passively is not enough. Watching the recording afterward and doing the exercises on your own is not enough because you lose access to the trainer who will help you when you get stuck. Also, I don’t believe anyone is watching those recordings.在研讨会期间练习只是一个起点。注册还不够。支付研讨会费用还不够。即使被动地参加和坐着也是不够的。之后观看录音并自己进行练习是不够的，因为当您遇到困难时，您将无法联系到可以帮助您的培训师。另外，我不相信有人在看这些录音。

The only way to learn automated testing is to learn the basics (for example, during a workshop) and practice it at work. Regardless of the testing technique, they choose to follow.学习自动化测试的唯一方法是学习基础知识（例如，在研讨会期间）并在工作中进行练习。无论测试技术如何，他们都会选择遵循。

Test-driven development in Jupyter NotebookJupyter Notebook 中的测试驱动开发

TDD for data scientists working with Jupyter Notebook面向使用 Jupyter Notebook 的数据科学家的 TDD
Bartosz Mikulski 22 Oct 2018 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 10 月 22 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

In the blog post “5 reasons why jupyter notebooks suck” Alexander Mueller complained that code written in notebooks is difficult to test.在博客文章“jupyter Notebooks 糟糕的 5 个原因”中，Alexander Mueller 抱怨用 Notebook 编写的代码很难测试。

Unfortunately, that is true, but I want to show you how to work around that issue and get something that resembles test-driven development in notebooks.不幸的是，这是事实，但我想向您展示如何解决该问题并获得类似于笔记本中的测试驱动开发的东西。

First of all, we must get used to the fact that there is no support for any testing library used in Python. The only things we can use, are the testing capabilities built-in Python, which means the “assert” keyword.首先，我们必须习惯Python中使用的任何测试库都不支持的事实。我们唯一可以使用的是Python内置的测试功能，这意味着“assert”关键字。

That’s it. The only thing we have is the ability to check if an expression returns True.就是这样。我们唯一拥有的是检查表达式是否返回 True 的能力。

The second problem is the way Jupyter displays assertion errors. It looks like every other type of error. We must get used to that too.第二个问题是 Jupyter 显示断言错误的方式。它看起来就像所有其他类型的错误。我们也必须习惯这一点。

There are dozens of books about test-driven development itself, so I am not going to focus on the method. Instead of that, I will show you the tools.关于测试驱动开发本身的书籍有几十本，因此我不会重点讨论该方法。相反，我将向您展示工具。

The “assert” keyword“断言”关键字

How does the “assert” work? The assert’s parameters consist of two parts. The first part is the boolean expression that is supposed to be True. The second parameter is the error message to be displayed if the boolean expression evaluates to False. We can use the second parameter to give the test a name or describe what should happen.“断言”如何发挥作用？断言的参数由两部分组成。第一部分是应该为 True 的布尔表达式。第二个参数是布尔表达式计算结果为 False 时显示的错误消息。我们可以使用第二个参数来给测试命名或描述应该发生的情况。

Let’s look at an example. In this case, the assertion fails, and we get an error.让我们看一个例子。在这种情况下，断言失败，我们得到一个错误。

def multiplyByTwo(x):
    return x * 3

assert multiplyByTwo(2) == 4, "2 multiplied by 2 should be equal 4"

Unfortunately, there is no way to get the value returned by the function and display it with the error message unless you call the same function twice.不幸的是，除非您两次调用同一个函数，否则无法获取函数返回的值并将其与错误消息一起显示。

def multiplyByTwo(x):
    return x * 3

assert multiplyByTwo(2) == 4, "2 multiplied by 2 should be equal 4, but the function returned: " +  str(multiplyByTwo(2))

It is trivial in this case, but if the function does some heavy computation may take some time to get the error message. You can avoid this problem by assigning the output to a variable and using the variable in the assert clause.在这种情况下这很简单，但如果函数执行一些繁重的计算，可能需要一些时间才能获取错误消息。您可以通过将输出分配给变量并在断言子句中使用该变量来避免此问题。

def multiplyByTwo(x):
    return x * 3

result = multiplyByTwo(2)
assert result == 4, "2 multiplied by 2 should be equal 4, but the function returned: " +  str(result)

What happens if the test passes? That is kind of sad, but it does not display anything.如果测试通过会发生什么？这有点悲伤，但它没有显示任何东西。

You won’t see a green progress bar or an encouraging message like: “All tests passed.” If you have done everything right, all you get is an empty output.您不会看到绿色进度条或诸如“所有测试均已通过”之类的鼓励消息。如果你做的一切都是正确的，你得到的只是一个空的输出。

Math数学 Data science数据科学

Minkowski distance explained闵可夫斯基距离解释

Manhattan distance, Euclidean distance, and Chebyshev distance are types of Minkowski distances曼哈顿距离、欧几里得距离和切比雪夫距离是闵可夫斯基距离的类型
Bartosz Mikulski 05 Jul 2019 – 3 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 7 月 5 日 – 阅读 3 分钟

Sometimes we want to measure how much things are similar to each other or how different they are. It happens not only when we use algorithms like k-NN classification or clustering.有时我们想要衡量事物之间有多少相似之处或有多少不同。这种情况不仅发生在我们使用 k-NN 分类或聚类等算法时。

When we measure the performance of any other machine learning algorithm or neural network which returns a complex value that can be “partially correct.” In those cases, we want to know how close the result is to the correct answer.当我们测量任何其他机器学习算法或神经网络的性能时，它会返回一个“部分正确”的复杂值。在这些情况下，我们想知道结果与正确答案的接近程度。

In this article, I am going to explain a few distance metrics. First, I am going to start with metrics based on Minkowski distance because we all understand them intuitively. In the upcoming articles, I will also show you how to measure the “distance” between sets of values and distance between sequences.在本文中，我将解释一些距离度量。首先，我将从基于 Minkowski 距离的度量开始，因为我们都直观地理解它们。在接下来的文章中，我还将向您展示如何测量值集之间的“距离”以及序列之间的距离。

Minkowski distance闵可夫斯基距离

When we think about distance, we usually imagine distances between cities. That is the most intuitive understanding of the distance concept. Fortunately, this example is perfect for explaining the constraints of Minkowski distances.当我们考虑距离时，我们通常会想象城市之间的距离。这就是对距离概念最直观的理解。幸运的是，这个例子非常适合解释闵可夫斯基距离的约束。

Normed vector space赋范向量空间

We can calculate Minkowski distance only in a normed vector space, which is a fancy way of saying: “in a space where distances can be represented as a vector that has a length.”我们只能在赋范向量空间中计算明可夫斯基距离，这是一种奇特的说法：“在距离可以表示为具有长度的向量的空间中。”

Let’s start by proving that a map is a vector space. If we take a map, we see that distances between cities are normed vector space because we can draw a vector that connects two cities on the map. We can combine multiple vectors to create a route that connects more than two cities. Now, the adjective “normed.” It means that the vector has its length and no vector has a negative length. That constraint is met too because if we draw a line between cities on the map, we can measure its length.让我们首先证明地图是向量空间。如果我们拿一张地图，我们会看到城市之间的距离是标准化的向量空间，因为我们可以在地图上绘制连接两个城市的向量。我们可以组合多个向量来创建连接两个以上城市的路线。现在，形容词“规范”。这意味着向量有其长度并且没有向量具有负长度。这个约束也得到满足，因为如果我们在地图上的城市之间画一条线，我们就可以测量它的长度。

Minkowski distance - requirements闵可夫斯基距离 - 要求

  1. The zero vector, 0, has zero length; every other vector has a positive length. If we look at a map, it is obvious. The distance from a city to the same city is zero because we don’t need to travel at all. The distance from a city to any other city is positive because we can’t travel -20 km.零向量 0 的长度为零；每个其他向量都有正长度。如果我们看一下地图，就很明显了。一个城市到同一城市的距离为零，因为我们根本不需要旅行。从一个城市到任何其他城市的距离都是正数，因为我们不能行驶 -20 公里。

  2. Multiplying a vector by a positive number changes its length without changing its direction We traveled 50 km North. If we travel 50 km more in the same direction, we will end up 100 km North. The direction does not change. Easy, isn’t it?将矢量乘以正数会改变其长度而不改变其方向 我们向北行驶了 50 公里。如果我们朝同一方向再行驶 50 公里，我们最终将向北行驶 100 公里。方向不会改变。很容易，不是吗？

  3. The shortest distance between any two points is a straight line (this is called Triangle inequality). I believe it is self-explanatory.任意两点之间的最短距离是一条直线（这称为三角不等式）。我相信这是不言自明的。

Minkowski distance types闵可夫斯基距离类型

There is only one equation for Minkowski distance, but we can parameterize it to get slightly different results.闵可夫斯基距离只有一个方程，但我们可以对其进行参数化以获得略有不同的结果。

Manhattan distance曼哈顿距离

It is the sum of absolute differences of all coordinates. It is a perfect distance measure for our example. When we can use a map of a city, we can give direction by telling people that they should walk/drive two city blocks North, then turn left and travel another three city blocks. In total they will travel five city blocks, that is the Manhattan distance between the starting point and their destination.它是所有坐标的绝对差之和。对于我们的例子来说，这是一个完美的距离测量。当我们可以使用城市地图时，我们可以通过告诉人们应该向北步行/驾车两个城市街区，然后左转并行驶另外三个城市街区来提供方向。他们总共将行驶五个城市街区，即起点和目的地之间的曼哈顿距离。

Euclidean distance欧氏距离

If we look again at the city block example used to explain the Manhattan distance, we see that the traveled path consists of two straight lines. When we draw another straight line that connects the starting point and the destination, we end up with a triangle. In this case, the distance between the points can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem.如果我们再次查看用于解释曼哈顿距离的城市街区示例，我们会发现行驶路径由两条直线组成。当我们绘制另一条连接起点和目的地的直线时，我们最终会得到一个三角形。在这种情况下，可以使用毕达哥拉斯定理来计算点之间的距离。

Chebyshev distance切比雪夫距离

It is the extreme case of Minkowski distance. When we use infinity as the value of the parameter p, we end up with a metric that defines distance as the maximal absolute difference between coordinates:这是闵可夫斯基距离的极端情况。当我们使用无穷大作为参数 p 的值时，我们最终得到一个将距离定义为坐标之间的最大绝对差的度量：

I wondered how it is used in practice and I found one example. In a warehouse, the distance between locations can be represented as Chebyshev distance if an overhead crane is used because the crane moves on both axes at the same time with the same speed.我想知道它在实践中是如何使用的，我找到了一个例子。在仓库中，如果使用桥式起重机，位置之间的距离可以表示为切比雪夫距离，因为起重机在两个轴上同时以相同的速度移动。

Precision vs. recall - explanation精确率与召回率 - 解释

How to understand the difference between precision and recall?如何理解准确率和召回率的区别？
Bartosz Mikulski 15 Jun 2018 – 4 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2018 年 6 月 15 日 – 阅读 4 分钟

Why couldn’t I remember the difference between precision and recall?为什么我记不住精确率和召回率之间的区别？

First of all, I had a problem with confusion matrix. The fact that the order of cells is different in textbooks and in the output produced by the tools we use was particularly problematic.首先，我遇到了混淆矩阵的问题。事实上，教科书上的单元顺序与我们使用的工具产生的输出不同，这是一个特别有问题的问题。

What is a column? Is it the actual value or the predicted value? Is true positive in the upper left cell or the lower right? I knew that both precision and recall are just rations between the confusion matrix cells, but which ones? It was kind of confusing ;)什么是柱？是实际值还是预测值？左上单元格还是右下单元格是真阳性？我知道精确率和召回率只是混淆矩阵单元之间的比例，但是是哪一个呢？这有点令人困惑;)

Precision/recall准确率/召回率

Fortunately, it is easy to understand precision and recall. Note I wrote: “understand.” I care about the intuition and understanding, not the calculation. You can always google the equation or just use your favourite tool to calculate that.幸运的是，精确度和召回率很容易理解。注意我写的是：“理解”。我关心的是直觉和理解，而不是计算。您始终可以通过谷歌搜索方程式，或者使用您最喜欢的工具来计算该方程式。

Imagine that a radar is a classifier. A classifier that classifies a point in space and returns one of two verdicts: “aircraft” or “empty.”想象一下雷达是一个分类器。对空间中的点进行分类并返回两个判断之一的分类器：“飞机”或“空”。

Let’s assume that we work for the army and we are supposed to build a radar (a classifier) to detect those airplanes.假设我们为军队工作，我们应该建造一个雷达（分类器）来检测这些飞机。

If we build a classifier which finds all airplanes and does not classify an empty point as an aircraft we have the following output.如果我们构建一个分类器来查找所有飞机并且不将空点分类为飞机，我们将得到以下输出。

It is a perfect classifier. Precision = 1, recall = 1 We have found all airplane and we have no false positives.这是一个完美的分类器。精度 = 1，召回率 = 1 我们已找到所有飞机，并且没有误报。

On the other hand, if we have an output which looks like this:另一方面，如果我们有一个如下所示的输出：

We have perfect precision once again. All points reported as an airplane are in fact airplanes. The only problem is a terrible recall. We have not found all airplanes. If those are enemy’s aircraft, we have a huge problem.我们再次拥有完美的精度。所有报告为飞机的点实际上都是飞机。唯一的问题是糟糕的回忆。我们还没有找到所有飞机。如果那些是敌人的飞机，我们就有一个大问题了。

There is one more mistake we can make. Is a classifier good enough if it finds all airplanes, but also reports a lot of empty spots as airplanes?我们还可能犯一个错误。如果分类器找到所有飞机，但也将许多空点报告为飞机，那么它是否足够好？

We detected all enemy aircraft. The only problem is, we waste a lot of jet fuel because we scramble our fighter aircraft way too often and they chase a non-existing enemy.我们检测到所有敌机。唯一的问题是，我们浪费了大量的喷气燃料，因为我们频繁地紧急升空战斗机，而它们却在追逐不存在的敌人。

What is more important? Precision or recall?更重要的是什么呢？精确率还是召回率？

There are two correct answers to that question:这个问题有两个正确答案：

  • both两个都

  • it depends这取决于

In the case of the radar, I assume we need to detect all airplanes, and we can accept some false positives. It is better to chase after a non-existing enemy than allow one of their aircraft to be not intercepted.就雷达而言，我假设我们需要检测所有飞机，并且我们可以接受一些误报。追击一个不存在的敌人比让他们的一架飞机不被拦截要好。

Tradeoff权衡

To prove that the tradeoff between precision and recall is, in fact, a business decision, let’s look at an example of a product that needs both precision and recall to be average.为了证明准确率和召回率之间的权衡实际上是一个商业决策，让我们看一个需要平均准确率和召回率的产品的示例。

What if we were developing a dating website? What if after registration your clients filled out a survey that you use to train a classifier. The classifier predicts whether another person is a good or bad match for that user. (Yes, I know. It is not the way such websites work. It doesn’t matter. I need an example ;) )如果我们正在开发一个约会网站怎么办？如果您的客户在注册后填写了一份用于训练分类器的调查，该怎么办？分类器预测另一个人是否适合该用户。 （是的，我知道。这不是此类网站的工作方式。没关系。我需要一个例子；））

We don’t want a perfect precision. If we had such classifier, the user would see only a few results (the ideal matches), found Mr. or Ms. Right immediately and never went back to your page. We don’t want that.我们不想要完美的精度。如果我们有这样的分类器，用户只会看到一些结果（理想的匹配），立即找到Mr. Right或Ms. Right，并且永远不会返回您的页面。我们不希望这样。

We can’t have too good recall either because it is always a tradeoff. Having the perfect recall would most likely require allowing many false positives (terrible precision). If you display many irrelevant results, the user will be disappointed and will run away to your competition.我们也不能拥有太好的回忆，因为这总是一个权衡。拥有完美的召回率很可能需要允许许多误报（精确度非常差）。如果您显示许多不相关的结果，用户将会感到失望，并会转向您的竞争对手。

What we want is precision/recall that gives the user some hope, so they return to your page every day and use it for as long as possible. Now you also know why dating websites are scam ;)我们想要的是精确度/召回率，给用户一些希望，这样他们每天都会回到你的页面并尽可能长时间地使用它。现在您也知道为什么约会网站是骗局了;)

To replace the ruined structures, the Polish People’s Republic rulers built Soviet-style housing blocks - gray monuments of sadness and despair. Nowadays, we paint them in bright colors in a futile attempt to make them look less like the human equivalent of battery cage poultry farms.这是一个充满旧唐楼的地区，底层是商店，上面是公寓。当然，并非所有人都在第二次世界大战中幸存下来。为了取代被毁坏的建筑，波兰人民共和国统治者建造了苏联风格的住宅区——悲伤和绝望的灰色纪念碑。如今，我们把它们涂成鲜艳的颜色，徒劳地试图让它们看起来不像人类的电池笼家禽养殖场。

To spice up the mix, we fill the unused space with ridiculously overpriced, modern apartment buildings with walls so thin you can hear the neighbors talking or flushing the toilet.为了让这种混合更加有趣，我们用价格高得离谱的现代公寓楼填充了未使用的空间，这些公寓楼的墙壁很薄，你可以听到邻居说话或冲厕所的声音。

This is fun! Seriously! I love it! But only if it happens once every 20-30 minutes. Not all the time for 4 hours.这个很有趣！严重地！我喜欢它！但前提是这种情况每 20-30 分钟发生一次。不是每次都4个小时。

Our adventure got even more exciting when a thunderstorm started in the middle of the trip.当旅途中途出现雷雨时，我们的冒险变得更加令人兴奋。

So here I was. In the middle of the forest. Underneath the trees. Standing in the water. During a thunderstorm.所以我就在这里。在森林中央。在树下。站在水中。雷阵雨期间。

I was a scout as a 9-10-year-old child. If I recall my training correctly, the only thing I could do to make the situation worse was holding a five-meter-high metal pole in my hands.我在 9 至 10 岁的时候曾是一名童子军。如果我没记错的话，我唯一能让情况变得更糟的就是手里拿着一根五米高的金属杆。

We were lucky that day, and nobody got hurt. However, the other data scientist somehow managed to soak his mobile phone in an almost dried-out river.那天我们很幸运，没有人受伤。然而，另一位数据科学家不知何故设法将他的手机浸入一条几乎干涸的河流中。

Every following day must be better after such a first week at work. One may think…经过第一周的工作后，接下来的每一天都一定会更好。有人可能会认为……

The task任务

Our startup’s founders couldn’t claim they were “making the world a better place,” “disrupting,” or “revolutionizing” anything.我们初创公司的创始人不能声称他们正在“让世界变得更美好”、“颠覆”或“彻底改变”任何事物。

We were running websites with celebrity gossip, trivia, crime stories, etc., selling advertisement space.我们经营有关名人八卦、琐事、犯罪故事等的网站，出售广告空间。

Was this a viable business? Hell no. Almost nobody looks for such websites, so we had to buy tons of ads elsewhere to get any traffic. The idea was based on the old-school concept of buying low and selling high.这是一项可行的业务吗？一定不行。几乎没有人寻找此类网站，因此我们不得不在其他地方购买大量广告才能获得流量。这个想法是基于低买高卖的老派概念。

They needed data scientists for the “buying low” part. We were trying to automate bidding and get as cheap traffic as possible.他们需要数据科学家来完成“低价买入”部分。我们试图自动化出价并获得尽可能便宜的流量。

Why was I working there?我为什么在那里工作？

It was the only place where an inexperienced data scientist could get a job. We all already know why the experienced people didn’t want it.这是没有经验的数据科学家可以找到工作的唯一地方。我们都知道为什么有经验的人不想要它。

Overall, was it a good business idea? Of course not. We were burning money fast. It was so bad we were celebrating every day when we managed to break even. It happened only once during my two months at this startup.总的来说，这是一个好的商业想法吗？当然不是。我们烧钱的速度很快。当我们设法实现收支平衡时，我们每天都在庆祝，这真是太糟糕了。在我在这家初创公司的两个月里，这种情况只发生过一次。

I know, I know. This is how startups work. It is true, but usually, startups pivot when their idea doesn’t work. At this place, we were doubling down on things that didn’t work in the past and expected to get different results this time.我知道我知道。这就是初创公司的运作方式。确实如此，但通常情况下，初创公司在他们的想法行不通时就会转向。在这个地方，我们加倍努力做过去不起作用的事情，并期望这次能得到不同的结果。

Quickly, I realized I don’t enjoy training machine learning models nearly as much as I thought I would.很快，我意识到我并不像我想象的那样喜欢训练机器学习模型。

It was fun when I was learning it. Mostly because I was switching to a different problem every time I got a working solution. Not here. This was the real world, not a Kaggle assignment. I had one problem and one problem only: figure out the maximal amount we could spend on buying ads and still make a profit.我学的时候觉得很有趣。主要是因为每次我得到一个可行的解决方案时，我都会切换到不同的问题。不在这里。这是现实世界，而不是 Kaggle 作业。我遇到了一个问题，而且只有一个问题：计算出我们可以在购买广告上花费的最大金额，并且仍然可以盈利。

Worse still, I wasn’t as good a data scientist as I wish I had been.更糟糕的是，我并没有像我希望的那样成为一名优秀的数据科学家。

I realized I enjoy deploying the model and building data pipelines more than training the models.我意识到我更喜欢部署模型和构建数据管道，而不是训练模型。

Soon, I focused on doing the data engineering part of the job. Nobody complained because the other data scientist didn’t know how to do it. Others perceived my behavior as stepping up to a challenge, not hiding in the comfort zone. Only I knew the truth.很快，我就专注于工作中的数据工程部分。没有人抱怨，因为其他数据科学家不知道该怎么做。其他人认为我的行为是在迎接挑战，而不是躲在舒适区。只有我知道真相。

Quitting戒烟

At the same time, I read the “Career Superpowers” book by James A. Whittaker. In the book, he wrote the “Underachievement Manifesto,” saying:与此同时，我读了詹姆斯·A·惠特克（James A. Whittaker）的《职业超能力》一书。在书中，他写下了“成绩不佳宣言”，其中写道：

This may seem harsh, but there is opportunity written all over it for those who aren’t too blind with ambition to see it. The ranks of any fields, no matter how mundane or exciting, are full of people who have stretched to get there. People not quite smart enough for medicine still practice medicine. People not quite dedicated enough to law are still lawyers. People who aren’t particularly mechanically minded still try to fix cars. This is why a good mechanic stands out, he or she is competing against people who aren’t really good enough to be there.这可能看起来很残酷，但对于那些没有太盲目的野心而看不到它的人来说，其中充满了机会。任何领域的行列，无论多么平凡或令人兴奋，都充满了努力到达那里的人。那些不太聪明、不懂医学的人仍然行医。对法律不够热心的人仍然是律师。那些不太懂机械的人仍然会尝试修理汽车。这就是为什么优秀的机械师能够脱颖而出，他或她正在与那些不够优秀的人竞争。

That was me. I stretched to become a data scientist, and I didn’t even enjoy the job. Soon, I switched to data engineering/MLOps and never looked back.那是我。我努力成为一名数据科学家，但我什至不喜欢这份工作。很快，我转向了数据工程/MLOps，并且再也没有回头。

When I handed in my resignation, the team couldn’t understand why I quit a company where I could influence the product and do whatever I wanted (as long as it was related to buying cheaper ads).当我递交辞呈时，团队无法理解为什么我要退出一家我可以影响产品并做任何我想做的事情（只要与购买更便宜的广告有关）的公司。

Partially, this was the problem. Everyone was doing whatever they wanted (including the founders) instead of trying to earn money for the company. Apparently, having a startup or being employed in one was more important than making it a successful business.部分地，这就是问题所在。每个人（包括创始人）都在做他们想做的事，而不是试图为公司赚钱。显然，拥有一家初创公司或受雇于一家初创公司比使其成为一家成功的企业更重要。

I told them I didn’t believe they could survive the next six months. I was wrong. They went out of business after eight months.我告诉他们我不相信他们能活过接下来的六个月。我错了。八个月后他们就倒闭了。

I didn’t include the data scientist job in my CV or LinkedIn profile. I am pretty ashamed of it. Most people don’t notice the gap or assume I took a long vacation between the jobs.我没有在我的简历或 LinkedIn 个人资料中包含数据科学家的职位。我对此感到非常羞愧。大多数人没有注意到这种差距，或者认为我在工作之间休了很长的假期。

If anybody asks, I tell them this story. So far, nobody has questioned my decision.如果有人问起，我就会告诉他们这个故事。到目前为止，没有人质疑我的决定。

Data Science数据科学

Why most data science projects fail?为什么大多数数据科学项目都会失败？

What are the biggest challenges in data science?数据科学中最大的挑战是什么？
Bartosz Mikulski 03 Jul 2019 – 4 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 7 月 3 日 – 阅读 4 分钟

In September 2015, Gartner published an article in which they predicted that: “through 2017, 60 percent of big data projects will fail to go beyond piloting and experimentation, and will be abandoned.” That is a massive number of project. Think about all the wasted effort, time, and money.2015年9月，Gartner发表文章预测：“到2017年，60%的大数据项目将无法超越试点和实验，并将被放弃。”这是一个庞大的项目。想想所有浪费的精力、时间和金钱。

It is hard to tell if they were right, but for sure many data projects has failed. Perhaps not all of them were called “big data projects.” Probably, way more than 60% of projects failed. It is even possible that some people did not even realize that their project had failed.很难判断他们是否正确，但可以肯定的是，许多数据项目都失败了。也许并非所有项目都被称为“大数据项目”。可能超过 60% 的项目都失败了。甚至有可能有些人甚至没有意识到他们的项目失败了。

In 2017, Kaggle published their first data science survey. One of the asked questions is: “At work, which barriers or challenges have you faced this past year?”2017 年，Kaggle 发布了第一份数据科学调查。其中一个问题是：“在工作中，您在过去的一年中遇到了哪些障碍或挑战？”

People pointed out a diverse set of reasons, such as:人们指出了各种各样的原因，例如：

  • Lack of data science talent in the organization组织中缺乏数据科学人才

  • Company politics / Lack of management/financial support for a data science team公司政治/数据科学团队缺乏管理/财务支持

  • Unavailability of/difficult access to data数据不可用/访问困难

  • Data Science results not used by business decision makers业务决策者未使用数据科学结果

  • Lack of significant domain expert input缺乏重要的领域专家的意见

  • Limitations of tools工具的限制

  • Need to coordinate with IT需要与IT协调

  • Lack of funds to buy useful datasets from external sources缺乏资金从外部来源购买有用的数据集

  • Difficulties in deployment/scoring部署/评分困难

  • Limitations in state of the art in machine learning机器学习最新技术的局限性

For me, the most surprising was: “The lack of a clear question to be answering or a clear direction to go in with the available data.”对我来说，最令人惊讶的是：“缺乏需要回答的明确问题或可用数据的明确方向。”

The one problem唯一的问题

Honestly, I think it is the reason why most projects fail. It is all about setting the goal. If you decide what questions you want to answer or what you want to achieve dealing with other problems becomes significantly easier.老实说，我认为这就是大多数项目失败的原因。这一切都是为了设定目标。如果您决定要回答什么问题或要实现什么目标，那么处理其他问题就会变得容易得多。

The goal helps you decide what skills are required, so you know who should be hired for the job. Hence lack of skills should no longer be a problem.该目标可帮助您决定需要哪些技能，以便您知道应该雇用谁来完成这项工作。因此，缺乏技能不再是问题。

Lack of management/financial support is way easier to overcome when the desired outcome is known. You can make a plan, decide who should be involved in the project, and even estimate the required budget.当期望的结果已知时，管理/财务支持的缺乏就更容易克服。您可以制定计划，决定谁应该参与该项目，甚至估算所需的预算。

If you can’t tell what the purpose of a project is, it may indicate that the project does not support any of the business goals. It should not be a surprise that business decision makers did not use such a project.如果您无法判断项目的目的是什么，则可能表明该项目不支持任何业务目标。商业决策者没有使用这样的项目并不奇怪。

Problems related to cooperation with other teams, lack of funds, or limited access to experts don’t exist when you have a clear goal that supports the primary purpose of the business because such initiatives typically have both management support and huge budgets.当您有支持业务主要目的的明确目标时，与其他团队合作、缺乏资金或接触专家机会有限等相关问题就不存在，因为此类举措通常有管理支持和巨额预算。

Conclusion结论

I am not saying that having a purpose and knowing what you want to achieve magically solves all of your problems. No. It does not, but without a goal, you don’t even know what problems you have, so good lack solving any of them.我并不是说有一个目标并知道你想要实现什么就可以神奇地解决你所有的问题。不，不是的，但是如果没有目标，你甚至不知道自己有什么问题，所以也无法解决其中的任何问题。

It is easy to fail a project if you have no idea what you want to achieve. What if 60% percent of projects which were predicted to fail shouldn’t have been started in the first place? What if the outcome of those projects didn’t matter because they were trying to solve an issue that looked cool but were irrelevant from the perspective of the whole business?如果您不知道自己想要实现什么目标，那么项目很容易失败。如果 60% 预计失败的项目一开始就不应该启动怎么办？如果这些项目的结果并不重要，因为它们试图解决一个看起来很酷但从整个业务的角度来看无关紧要的问题怎么办？

Perhaps we should ask “why” more often. After all, curiosity is the fundamental trait of a scientist, and many of us dare to call themselves data scientists. It is not just a trendy job description. Those words have actual meaning, and people have some expectations when they hear them.也许我们应该多问“为什么”。毕竟，好奇心是科学家的基本特质，我们中的许多人都敢于称自己为数据科学家。这不仅仅是一个流行的职位描述。这句话是有实际意义的，人们听了都会有一些期待。

Everything gets easier when you have a goal which you deeply understand. We should not only know what we are doing but also know all of the reasons and the context.当你有一个深刻理解的目标时，一切都会变得更容易。我们不仅应该知道我们在做什么，还应该知道所有的原因和背景。

To achieve that, we must be interested not only in data science techniques and tools but also in business. We must know not only how the company operates, but also understand how the whole industry works.为了实现这一目标，我们不仅必须对数据科学技术和工具感兴趣，而且还必须对商业感兴趣。我们不仅要了解公司如何运作，还要了解整个行业如何运作。

Additionally, we must be aware of company politics because sometimes projects are started when the Big Boss with Big Ego wants an extraordinary success just to brag in front of the Board of directors. That is ok too! As long as you know about the real purpose and understand how it affects you.此外，我们必须了解公司政治，因为有时项目是在自负的大老板想要取得非凡成功时启动的，只是为了在董事会面前吹嘘。那也可以！只要您了解真正的目的并了解它如何影响您。
