Notetaking for data science数据科学笔记

How to document a project?如何记录项目？
Bartosz Mikulski 12 Jun 2019 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 6 月 12 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

I was looking for a suitable method of taking notes during exploratory data analysis. I needed something that imposes enough structure to have all the essential aspects are covered. Something that makes it impossible to make a silly mistake and omit important information.我一直在寻找一种在探索性数据分析过程中记笔记的合适方法。我需要一些具有足够结构的东西来涵盖所有基本方面。这使得不可能犯愚蠢的错误并遗漏重要信息。

At the same time, I did not want anything as formal as the laboratory notebook used by scientists working in laboratories. In my opinion, that would be an overkill.同时，我不想要像在实验室工作的科学家使用的实验室笔记本这样正式的东西。在我看来，这太过分了。

Obviously, the best kind of documentation is the code. It covers the reproducibility requirement and cannot be misinterpreted. It is almost perfect.显然，最好的文档是代码。它涵盖了再现性要求并且不能被误解。它几乎是完美的。

Sadly, the code does not explain why it was written. It does not reveal its purpose. It does not explain the decision made by the author.遗憾的是，该代码没有解释为什么要编写它。它没有透露其目的。它没有解释作者所做的决定。

It is even worse when I read my code written six months ago. I see that I have generated a chart and decided to remove outliers from the dataset. What if it took me three days to conclude that the outliers should be removed? What if I had to dig in the source code of the application that implements the business process which generates the data? Well, I would probably remember that after six months.当我读到六个月前写的代码时，情况更糟。我看到我已经生成了一个图表并决定从数据集中删除异常值。如果我花了三天时间才得出应该删除异常值的结论怎么办？如果我必须挖掘实现生成数据的业务流程的应用程序的源代码怎么办？嗯，六个月后我可能会记住这一点。

Nevertheless, we should not rely on our memory. People forget things. People quit. People recall things that did not happen or happened on a different occasion. We don’t even know that some of our “memories” are fake.然而，我们不应该依赖我们的记忆。人们会忘记事情。人们放弃了。人们会回忆起未发生或在不同场合发生的事情。我们甚至不知道我们的一些“记忆”是假的。

We need a decent and straightforward method of documenting what we have done with data. Fortunately, there have been people who tried to write some suggestions about writing such documentation:我们需要一种体面而直接的方法来记录我们对数据所做的事情。幸运的是，有人尝试写一些关于编写此类文档的建议：

  • https://medium.com/outlier-bio-blog/a-quick-guide-to-organizing-data-science-projects-updated-for-2016-4cbb1e6dac71https://medium.com/outlier-bio-blog/a-quick-guide-to-organizing-data-science-projects-updated-for-2016-4cbb1e6dac71
  • https://github.com/rdpeng/courses/blob/master/05_ReproducibleResearch/Checklist/index.mdhttps://github.com/rdpeng/courses/blob/master/05_ReproducibleResearch/Checklist/index.md
  • https://towardsdatascience.com/building-an-end-to-end-data-science-project-28e853c0cae3https://towardsdatascience.com/building-an-end-to-end-data-science-project-28e853c0cae3
  • https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000424https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000424
  • https://www.kdnuggets.com/2018/07/cookiecutter-data-science-organize-data-project.htmlhttps://www.kdnuggets.com/2018/07/cookiecutter-data-science-organize-data-project.html
  • https://www.carlboettiger.info/2012/05/06/research-workflow.htmlhttps://www.carlboettiger.info/2012/05/06/research-workflow.html

Summary概括

In general, the guidelines and best practices I have found so far suggest:总的来说，我迄今为止发现的指南和最佳实践建议：

  • keeping the input data separated from code and the results将输入数据与代码和结果分开

  • using names that indicate the order of running files, such as 001_merge_input.py, 002_validate_data.py, etc.使用指示文件运行顺序的名称，例如 001_merge_input.py、002_validate_data.py 等。

  • writing down the purpose of the analysis, the author’s name and the name of the person who will be using the result写下分析的目的、作者姓名和结果使用人的姓名

  • making a list of all the data sources (including the queries used to retrieve them)列出所有数据源（包括用于检索它们的查询）

  • noting the purpose and reason of every step, before writing the code.在编写代码之前注意每一步的目的和原因。

  • separating experiments. One hypothesis per file. Keep all the files, especially if the result is not what you expected.分离实验。每个文件一个假设。保留所有文件，特别是如果结果不是您所期望的。

  • if something is strange or something surprised you, write it down.如果有什么奇怪的事情或令你惊讶的事情，请写下来。

  • if you needed to ask someone for an explanation, write it down如果您需要向某人寻求解释，请写下来

  • keep all your files in a code repository like Git or Subversion将所有文件保存在 Git 或 Subversion 等代码存储库中

  • no manual steps, everything must be automated. If the script requires some initial state, it should either prepare it or at least validate whether the initial conditions are met.没有手动步骤，一切都必须自动化。如果脚本需要某种初始状态，它应该准备它或者至少验证是否满足初始条件。

  • keep track of the software environment (automatically generate a list of libraries you used and their versions)跟踪软件环境（自动生成您使用的库及其版本的列表）

  • keep all versions of the output, write down the date when you produced them. 保留输出的所有版本，记下生成它们的日期。
    If you have sent a report to someone, keep it. Always. Even if one day later you had to change the code and create the report again, keep the old version.如果您已向某人发送报告，请保留该报告。总是。即使有一天您必须更改代码并再次创建报告，也请保留旧版本。

Data Science数据科学

Write everything down写下一切

Lessons learnt from "Practical Data Cleaning" by Lee Baker从 Lee Baker 的“实用数据清理”中汲取的经验教训
Bartosz Mikulski 24 May 2019 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 5 月 24 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

I have just finished reading “Practical Data Cleaning” by Lee Baker. I can’t recommend that book. It is too short and disappointingly basic. If you never worked with real-world data, if you worked only with ready-to-use Kaggle datasets, then maybe you can learn something from this book.我刚刚读完 Lee Baker 的《实用数据清理》。我不能推荐那本书。它太短而且基础得令人失望。如果您从未使用过现实世界的数据，如果您只使用过现成的 Kaggle 数据集，那么也许您可以从本书中学到一些东西。

I am disappointed, but there is one idea that cannot be stressed enough. One thing that should be repeated every single day until we all accept it as a regular daily practice. Writing things down!我很失望，但有一个想法怎么强调都不为过。一件事应该每天重复，直到我们都接受它作为日常惯例。把事情写下来！

Do you have a special value that indicates missing data? Write it down somewhere. Preferably in the code that cleans the dataset. Preferably as a constant with a name that conveys its meaning.您是否有指示缺失数据的特殊值？把它写在某处。最好在清理数据集的代码中。最好是作为一个常量，并具有传达其含义的名称。

We all “love” looking in the code for other usages of data we are trying to use because we hope that someone else has already figured out the meaning of values, don’t we?我们都“喜欢”在代码中查找我们尝试使用的数据的其他用法，因为我们希望其他人已经弄清楚了值的含义，不是吗？

We “love” when information about the data source is available two days a week when a colleague is in the office and has some spare time to answer our questions.我们“喜欢”每周两天有同事在办公室并且有空闲时间回答我们的问题时提供有关数据源的信息。

We “love” being surprised by a variable which has way too many values and they don’t mean what we expect. Lately, I came across data in which one variable indicated a boolean property, but surprisingly 1 meant “negative,” 0 meant “positive,” and there were values larger than 1 which I had to convert to 0 because for some time it was possible to choose more options, but people did not like it, so it was removed, but nobody updated the values in database.我们“喜欢”对具有太多值的变量感到惊讶，并且它们并不代表我们的预期。最近，我遇到了一些数据，其中一个变量表示布尔属性，但令人惊讶的是 1 表示“负”，0 表示“正”，并且存在大于 1 的值，我必须将其转换为 0，因为在一段时间内这是可能的选择更多选项，但人们不喜欢它，所以它被删除，但没有人更新数据库中的值。

How can we know about stuff like that if it is not written down anywhere? Please, please document the data. The next person (or you in 6 months) will be very, very grateful.如果没有任何地方记录下来，我们怎么能知道类似的事情呢？请记录数据。下一个人（或者 6 个月后的你）将会非常非常感激。

If you find something strange and spend two days trying to find an explanation, don’t try to remember it, write it down. If you found incorrect data caused by a bug, write down some information about that bug. Or even better, write a (well-documented) function that converts the faulty data into something correct. If you get an explanation: “we have always been doing it like this, but nobody remembers why,” please dig down and find out why you are doing it.如果你发现一些奇怪的事情并花了两天时间试图找到解释，不要试图记住它，而是把它写下来。如果您发现错误导致的数据不正确，请记下有关该错误的一些信息。或者更好的是，编写一个（有详细记录的）函数，将错误数据转换为正确数据。如果你得到这样的解释：“我们一直都是这样做的，但没有人记得为什么”，请深入挖掘并找出你这样做的原因。

We don’t need data mythology. After all, we call the practice “data science” or “data engineering.” That should hold us to higher standards.我们不需要数据神话。毕竟，我们将这种实践称为“数据科学”或“数据工程”。这应该让我们达到更高的标准。

Data Science数据科学

Recommendations vs. raw data — what is better?建议与原始数据 — 哪个更好？

Should we suggest an action when we visualize data?当我们可视化数据时，我们应该建议采取行动吗？
Bartosz Mikulski 04 Mar 2019 – 2 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2019 年 3 月 4 日 – 阅读 2 分钟

Is it better to show the users recommendations or raw data? On the one hand, raw data allows them to make their conclusions. It gives them control. It may even give people the satisfaction of discovering some insights, even if those insights very obvious. On the other hand, what if you want them to do a specific action and they misinterpret the data?向用户展示建议还是原始数据更好？一方面，原始数据使他们能够得出结论。它给了他们控制权。它甚至可以让人们因发现一些见解而感到满足，即使这些见解非常明显。另一方面，如果您希望他们执行特定操作而他们误解了数据怎么办？

In the “Data Nerdism at Large” episode of the DataFramed podcast, Mara Averick says that data visualization can be helpful and misleading at the same time.在 DataFramed 播客的“Data Nerdism at Large”一集中，Mara Averick 表示，数据可视化可能会有所帮助，但同时也会产生误导。

Example例子

She talks about a study of the toxicity of chemicals which polluted one community.她谈到了一项对污染一个社区的化学物质的毒性的研究。

After the study, the researchers showed the people a scatter plot with a line which marks the threshold at which the substances become cancerogenic. On the same chart, there were points which represented other people in the study and the one point that represented the household of the person who was looking at the chart.研究结束后，研究人员向人们展示了一张散点图，其中的一条线标记了这些物质致癌的阈值。在同一张图表上，有一些点代表研究中的其他人，还有一个点代表正在查看图表的人的家庭。

Surprisingly often, somebody who was way, way above the threshold did not worry about it as long as they saw that they were below other houses in their neighborhood.令人惊讶的是，通常，那些远远高于门槛的人只要看到自己低于附近其他房屋，就不会担心这一点。

Problem问题

What problem does it show? There are two ways of looking at this situation. Which one you choose is in my opinion strongly correlated with your place on the political spectrum, but I cannot prove that.它显示出什么问题？有两种方式看待这种情况。我认为你选择哪一个与你在政治领域的地位密切相关，但我无法证明这一点。

What if the people understood the significance of that information, but they ignored it because that was a more comfortable approach? They saw that other people are in a worse situation. That justified their lack of action, so they anchored to that information and neglected everything else.如果人们理解该信息的重要性，但他们忽略它，因为这是一种更舒服的方法，该怎么办？他们看到其他人的处境更糟。这证明他们缺乏行动是合理的，因此他们只关注这些信息而忽略了其他一切。

Maybe we have a problem with understanding that if we are dying it does not matter that other people are dying faster.也许我们在理解上存在问题，即如果我们快要死了，其他人死得更快并不重要。

That is one explanation. Let’s look at the second one.这是一种解释。我们看第二个。

What if the people who participated in the study understood the data, knew that they have a huge problem, but for some reason were unable to deal with it, so they were looking for something that gave them hope?如果参与研究的人了解这些数据，知道他们有一个巨大的问题，但由于某种原因无法处理它，所以他们正在寻找能给他们带来希望的东西，该怎么办？

What if the only recommendation they could get was “move somewhere else”? If they live in such a nasty area, we can assume that moving out was beyond their ability. What if they ignore the advice because they cannot afford to take action?如果他们能得到的唯一建议是“搬到其他地方”怎么办？如果他们住在这样一个肮脏的地区，我们可以假设搬出去超出了他们的能力。如果他们因为无力采取行动而忽视建议怎么办？

Recommendation vs. raw data建议与原始数据

That brings us back to the original question. Is it better to show raw data or to give recommendations?这让我们回到了最初的问题。是显示原始数据更好还是给出建议更好？

In my opinion, we should offer a summary of the data (perhaps in the form of a recommendation), the raw data, and some explanation of the process we followed to get the recommendation. It seems that we should emphasize the importance of explainability not only in machine learning models, but also in data visualizations.在我看来，我们应该提供数据摘要（也许以建议的形式）、原始数据以及我们获得建议所遵循的过程的一些解释。看来我们不仅应该在机器学习模型中强调可解释性的重要性，还应该在数据可视化中强调可解释性的重要性。

Most importantly, we should never judge the consumers of our recommendations. They are doing what is best for them. Even if their definition of “best” is entirely different than ours.最重要的是，我们永远不应该根据我们的建议来评判消费者。他们正在做对他们最有利的事情。即使他们对“最好”的定义与我们的完全不同。

Data engineering数据工程

Definition of done for data engineers数据工程师完成的定义

When can data engineers be sure that they have done the task?数据工程师什么时候才能确定他们已经完成了任务？
Bartosz Mikulski 14 Jan 2021 – 4 min read 巴托斯·米库尔斯基 2021 年 1 月 14 日 – 阅读 4 分钟

In every team’s life, there is a day when they finally decide to write a definition of done. Usually, it happens after a significant misunderstanding. For example, the team deployed a subpar feature, and they had not even noticed that something was missing. A manager, the client, or the product owner called a meeting and said, “Isn’t it obvious that…?” Well, it wasn’t obvious.在每个团队的生命中，总有一天他们最终决定写下“完成”的定义。通常，这种情况发生在重大误会之后。例如，团队部署了一个低于标准的功能，他们甚至没有注意到缺少了一些东西。经理、客户或产品负责人召开会议并说：“这不是很明显吗……？”嗯，这并不明显。

It starts as an innocent meeting. After all, the first line in the definition of done is usually “The code fulfills the acceptance criteria of the user story.” Fair enough. The code should work as expected, so there is nothing unusual about this sentence.它从一次无辜的会议开始。毕竟，完成定义中的第一行通常是“代码满足用户故事的验收标准”。很公平。代码应该按预期工作，因此这句话没有什么异常。

How does it happen that we often end up with “definitions of done,” which tell us that the code must be reviewed, merged, and deployed? Is it a result of peer pressure? You have to say something, and the only thing that counts as a contribution is adding a new item to the laundry list of requirements. Apparently, staying quiet and not making the mess does not matter. In the end, we have a long useless document. Nobody remembers its content, and we never look at it again.为什么我们经常会得到“完成的定义”，它告诉我们必须审查、合并和部署代码？这是同侪压力的结果吗？你必须说点什么，唯一算作贡献的就是在需求清单中添加一个新项目。显然，保持安静和不制造混乱并不重要。最后，我们得到了一份又长又无用的文件。没有人记得它的内容，我们也不会再看它。

The code works as expected代码按预期工作

In this article, I will derive a reasonable definition of done for a data engineering team starting from a simple yet fundamental requirement that “The code works as expected.”在本文中，我将从“代码按预期工作”这一简单而基本的要求出发，为数据工程团队得出“完成”的合理定义。

What does it mean? First of all, we have an underlying assumption that we know what the expected output is. Then, we have to test it somehow and prove to others that the code works correctly.这是什么意思？首先，我们有一个基本假设，即我们知道预期输出是什么。然后，我们必须以某种方式测试它并向其他人证明代码可以正常工作。

We will most likely write an automated test to verify the acceptance criteria, but we don’t need to state that in the document. Of course, we will write way more tests to verify the individual chunks of code, but, to be honest, nobody cares about that. The tests are for the developers. We will not put unit testing in the document either.我们很可能会编写一个自动化测试来验证验收标准，但我们不需要在文档中说明这一点。当然，我们将编写更多的测试来验证各个代码块，但是，说实话，没有人关心这一点。测试是针对开发人员的。我们也不会在文档中放入单元测试。

The code will work as expected in the future该代码将来将按预期工作

If the requirements have not changed, the behavior of the code should not change either. Again, we need automated tests to ensure that but, in data engineering, testing the code is not enough! What if the input data changes? What if we get a field in a different format, empty fields, or the distribution of values changes?如果需求没有改变，代码的行为也不应该改变。同样，我们需要自动化测试来确保，但是，在数据工程中，测试代码是不够的！如果输入数据发生变化怎么办？如果我们得到不同格式的字段、空字段或值的分布发生变化怎么办？

The requirement that the code works as expected implies that we can monitor the behavior in production and get a notification when something weird happens.代码按预期工作的要求意味着我们可以监视生产中的行为并在发生奇怪情况时收到通知。

What else do we need? We need tests, which are good enough to detect unintended behavior change when someone modifies another part of the code. In this case, the test is our last line of defense that prevents an error. Maybe we can be a little bit proactive here. What if we write extensive documentation that describes the feature and architecture decisions that we have made? Proper documentation may prevent a lot of errors and questions in the future. Therefore, writing and updating the documentation should also be a part of our definition of done.我们还需要什么？我们需要测试，当有人修改代码的另一部分时，测试足以检测出意外的行为变化。在这种情况下，测试是我们防止错误的最后一道防线。也许我们可以在这里采取主动一点。如果我们编写大量文档来描述我们所做的功能和架构决策会怎么样？正确的文档可以防止将来出现很多错误和问题。因此，编写和更新文档也应该成为我们“完成”定义的一部分。

What do others expect?其他人期望什么？

What else do we expect? Hopefully, other teams use the code we wrote or the data we produce. They have some expectations too. Hence, we should notify everyone who may be affected by the changes we have made.我们还期待什么？希望其他团队使用我们编写的代码或我们生成的数据。他们也有一些期待。因此，我们应该通知所有可能受到我们所做更改影响的人。

We will probably not forget to send messages to other teams when we modify a table structure or a data format. What about changes that affect performance? What if someone needs a report at 9 am, but our change causes a two-hour delay? Because of that, awareness of code performance should also be a part of our definition of done.当我们修改表结构或数据格式时，我们可能不会忘记向其他团队发送消息。那么影响性能的变化又如何呢？如果有人需要在上午 9 点提交报告，但我们的更改导致了两个小时的延迟怎么办？因此，对代码性能的认识也应该成为我们“完成”定义的一部分。

Last but not least, the CFO expects that we have the costs under control. If our cloud costs double suddenly, can we say that the code works as expected? In my opinion, we can make a reasonable assumption that the data engineering team should know how their changes affect the amount paid for the infrastructure and storage.最后但并非最不重要的一点是，首席财务官希望我们能够控制成本。如果我们的云成本突然翻倍，我们可以说代码按预期工作吗？在我看来，我们可以做出合理的假设，即数据工程团队应该知道他们的更改如何影响基础设施和存储的支付金额。

The definition of done for a data engineering team数据工程团队“完成”的定义

What do we get when we summarize all of those expectations? Here is my definition of done:当我们总结所有这些期望时，我们会得到什么？这是我对完成的定义：

  1. The code works as expected.该代码按预期工作。
  2. The code works as expected, which is confirmed by automated tests that verify the acceptance criteria.该代码按预期工作，这通过验证验收标准的自动化测试得到了证实。
  3. The code will work as expected in the future. Therefore, we monitor vital metrics and have defined alerts that notify us when the expectations are not met. We have also written enough automated tests to detect any unintended change of behavior.该代码将来将按预期工作。因此，我们监控重要指标并定义警报，以便在未达到预期时通知我们。我们还编写了足够的自动化测试来检测任何意外的行为变化。
  4. We will always understand what is the expected behavior of the code. To ensure that, we have written and updated the documentation.我们将始终了解代码的预期行为是什么。为了确保这一点，我们编写并更新了文档。
  5. Others know that the code works as expected. We have notified everyone who may be affected by the code changes, and the solution does not violate SLA (it is not too slow, and the cost does not exceed the budget).其他人知道代码按预期工作。我们已经通知了所有可能受到代码变更影响的人，并且解决方案不违反SLA（也不算太慢，成本不超出预算）。
